<TITLE>LIMITS Project</TITLE>
<H1>L.I.M.I.T.S. PROJECT:</H1>
<H2>Linking Important Medical Information To Students</H2>
<HR>
<H3>Project Faculty</H3>
<UL>
<LI>Gary P. Barnas, M.D., Associate Professor, Division of General Internal Medicine and Medical Informatics
<LI>James R. Zeller, M.D., Associate Professor, Division of General Internal Medicine
<LI>Mary Blackwelder, Director, MCW Library 
<LI>Ondrej Zoltan, MCW Library Information Systems
</UL><HR>
<H3>Background</H3><PRE>
Medical students can be overwhelmed by the medical information 
explosion and ever expanding medical literature. While the availability 
of the Medline database has improved accessibility to the literature, it 
has not aided the student in distilling the relevant information from the 
unimportant or erroneous literature. Many poorly designed research 
studies may still reach publication and need to be interpreted with 
caution. <A NAME="CITE1" HREF= "#REF1">Prior studies</A> [1-3] have also questioned the ability of students 
to perform effective Medline searches. Medline does not attempt to 
prioritize information on either importance or relevance to the topic of 
interest. A typical Medline search on a common medical problem or illness 
may retrieve over 100 articles that a student would need to sort through 
to hopefully find several key articles of interest. <A NAME="CITE4" HREF= "#REF4">Larry Weed</A> [4] described 
the need for Problem-Knowledge coupling to link relevant literature to 
common clinical problems seen in everyday medical practice.  Medical 
students would be ideal candidates to use such a system since their own 
medical knowledge is limited and their judgment may not be sufficiently 
developed at this early point in their careers to be able to sort and 
prioritize relevant medical literature that they may encounter. 

</PRE>
<H3>Rationale</H3><PRE>
The LIMITS project is an attempt to create a new method of providing access 
to relevant medical literature by establishing a linkage between clinical 
problems and the literature. In the past, attempts have been made to create 
such information resources through the use of article files maintained by 
faculty or chief residents on various clinical topics. These files frequently 
became outdated and were often inaccessible, frequently being locked up in 
an office filing cabinet. Other attempts have included article handouts or 
bibliographies frequently included in a course syllabus. However, these 
are usually lost or filed away and are not accessible when clinical problems 
arise and the literature is needed. The purpose of the LIMITS project is to 
overcome these previous obstacles and provide readily accessible 
information 24 hours a day to any geographic location with computer access. 
This would be especially useful for off campus clinical rotations. 

</PRE>
<H3>Description</H3><PRE>
The LIMITS project consists of a core database of annotated references to 
the medical literature with links to common medical problems and the 
Medline database. This linkage will be dynamically structured to provide 
for regular updating and provide a flexible way to index the information. 
For example, for a particular disease you may have a "table of contents" 
and then be able to choose an article on "diagnosis" or "treatment" of the 
condition. A "hypertext" capability could be used that would enable a user 
to select directly on those terms to link to an article.  In addition, the 
database may simultaneously have hypertext links to a course syllabus 
covering several different clinical problems that a student could search 
from. Thus, this system would allow for multiple "front-ends" to the 
article database. The database would also be accessible through boolean 
type "key word" searching used to access the traditional Medline database, 
or even a possible WAIS interface (Wide Area Information Server -  an 
indexed distributed text based search system). Future additions may 
include linkage to the controlled vocabulary of the NLM Metatheasaurus. 
Linkage to Medline may include pointers to U.I. (unique identifier) numbers. 
In addition to providing links to the relevant literature, provisions will 
be made to allow annotations or comments to be appended to the links 
to further clarify the usefulness or relevance of a particular article.

A pilot project has been funded by the MCW Learning Resources Subcomittee.
This will consist of indexing 500 core articles on 80-100 common clinical 
problems with selected annotations. These articles would be selected by the 
project faculty in cooperation with the clinical faculty, Chief Residents and 
student Clerkship Directors. If this project is successful, this could be 
expanded to additional problem areas while the existing indexed material is 
revised and updated as needed. In the future, we plan a WWW forms based 
interface to submit additional articles for  addition to this database.

</PRE>
<H3>Evaluation Strategy</H3><PRE>
We will assess the effectiveness of this project through the tracking of 
usage throughout the project period. A mechanism for immediate on-line 
user feedback through electronic mail (e-mail) will be made available. At 
the end of the project period, a survey instrument will be used to obtain 
user feedback and assess the utility of the information provided by this 
system in relation to the various student rotations. Course directors will 
also be surveyed to determine the degree to which use of this system was 
incorporated into their course curricula.

</PRE>
<H3>References</H3>
<OL>
<LI><A NAME="REF1"></A>Pao ML, Grefsheim SF, Barclay ML, and Shipman BL.  Student use of MEDLINE: an analysis of the effects of experience and searching knowledge and skills on retrieval in a clinical situation. Proceedings of the Annual Symposium on Computer Applications in Medical Care: 478-82, 1992.<A HREF="#CITE1"> [Return]</A>

<LI>Mitchell JA, Johnson ED, Hewett JE, and Proud VK.  Medical students using Grateful 	Med: analysis of failed searches and a six-month follow-up study. Computers & 	Biomedical Research. 25(1):43-55, 1992 Feb.<A HREF="#CITE1"> [Return]</A>

<LI>Mitchell JA,  Johnson ED, and  Proud VK.  New thoughts about medical students as 	effective searchers of MEDLINE. Academic Medicine.  65(7):434-7, 1990 Jul.<A HREF="#CITE1"> [Return]</A>

<LI><A NAME="REF4"></A>Weed LL, Knowledge coupling : new premises and new tools for medical care and 	education. New York : Springer-Verlag, 1991.<A HREF="#CITE4"> [Return]</A></OL><HR><A HREF="gopher://141.106.32.47/1MacintoshHD%3aLibrary%3aLIMITS%3a">Go to LIMITS Demo</A><HR>
