        width="100%">
            <tr>
                <td valign="top" width="100%"><font
                color="#804040" size="2" face="Arial">The Federal
                Trade Commission reports that Americans are
                losing $1,000,000,000 [one billion dollars] a
                year to investment swindlers and according to the
                Los Angeles Times, &quot;California and New York
                have the most stock brokers but the weakest
                regulatory systems. In fact, California ceased to
                license brokers in 1980.&quot; </font><p><font
                color="#804040" size="2" face="Arial">The North
                American Securities Administrators Association is
                concerned that &quot;the retirement nest eggs of
                Americans are in danger of being scrambled today
                by an alarming surge in investment schemes&quot;
                and the American Association of Retired Persons
                confirms: &quot;while people over the age of 65
                constitute only 12 percent of the population,
                they probably make up 30 percent of scam
                victims.&quot;</font><font face="Arial"> </font></p>
                <p><font color="#804040" size="2" face="Arial">Clearly
                the federal Securities and Exchange Commission
                lacks the resources to fully investigate and
                prosecute every investment fraud case in the
                United States and under the law the overwhelming
                number of investment fraud cases are prosecuted
                by individuals, through private skilled
                attorneys, despite the efforts of market
                manipulators to deprecate the efforts of lawyers
                for consumers and small investors who seek to
                re-coup their losses as a result of corporate
                manipulation and artificially enhancement of
                stock prices through misrepresentation and fraud.</font>
                </p>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><a name="recentnews"><font size="4"><strong>Recent
        News</strong></font> </a></p>
        <p><strong>CAI WIRELESS SYSTEMS, INC. - </strong>On Nov.
        22, 1996 a class action was filed in the United States
        District Court for purchasers of CAI Wireless Systems,
        Inc. stock between May 23, 1996 and Oct. 29, 1996. The
        complaint alleges that corporate officers claimed the
        company would be developing wireless cable television
        systems and a high-speed wireless Internet system, but
        failed to disclose numerous technical, and regulatory
        problems which made the company's statements concerning
        its future profitability false and misleading and which
        resulted in artificially inflating the price of the
        company's stock to the detriment of its purchasers. </p>
        <p><strong>CAI WIRELESS SYSTEMS INC. - </strong>A class
        action was filed in the United States District Court for
        the Northern District of New York on behalf of all
        purchasers of CAI Wireless Systems Inc. common stock
        during the period May 23, 1996 through Dec. 13, 1996. The
        complaint alleges that CAI and certain officers,
        directors, and controlling shareholders of CAI violated
        the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 by issuing to the
        investing public false and misleading statements
        regarding, among other things, CAI's Wireless Internet
        access service and the company's business relationship
        with Bell Atlantic and NYNEX. These misstatements
        concerned the commercial readiness and prospects of the
        company's wireless access service, and the company's
        ability to deliver inexpensive digital signals to Bell
        Atlantic and NYNEX. The complaint alleges that as a
        result of these misrepresentations and omissions CAI's
        common stock price was artificially inflated.</p>
        <p><strong>CEDAR GROUP, INC.</strong> - On November 12,
        1996, a class action lawsuit was filed in the U.S.
        District Court on behalf of purchasers of the common
        stock of Cedar Group, Inc. between April 20, 1995 and May
        18, 1996. The complaint alleges that the defendants used
        inaccurate and misleading accounting practices,
        substantially overstated the value of contracts obtained
        by Dominion Bridge, Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary of
        Cedar Group, Inc. and as a result artificially inflated
        the value of Cedar<br>
        Group stock to the detriment of innocent purchasers. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>CELLNET DATA SYSTEMS, INC.</strong> - On Oct.
        31, 1996, a class action complaint on behalf of
        shareholders was filed in the Superior Court of
        California against the Company and the lead underwriter
        alleging that the Prospectus and Registration Statement
        of Sept. 26, 1996, under which the Company sold 5,000,000
        shares, contained materially misleading statements that
        artificially inflated the value of the offering and that
        the company failed to disclose that a major patent
        conflict with Itron, Inc. that would substantially impact
        both profits and operations was forthcoming. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>COMSHARE, INC.</strong> - On Aug. 21, 1996, a
        class action was filed alleging misrepresenting and fraud
        concerning Comshare's finances during April 17, 1996
        through Aug. 6, 1996. Unlike the reports made by company
        officials, officers and directors knew that goods shipped
        to customers were sold under special agreements which
        required that the sales not be posted as revenues under
        Comshare's internal policies. Nonetheless qualified sales
        were treated as actual sales and booked as profits. As a
        result the stock was sold to the public at artificially
        inflated prices from $22.00 to $23.00 per share;
        eventually the stock crashed to it real value of $11 per
        share. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>CREE RESEARCH, INC</strong>. - On Oct. 29,
        1996, a class action lawsuit was filed in the United
        States District Court on behalf of purchasers of Cree
        common stock between February 1, 1996 and July 2, 1996.
        The complaint charges Cree and its directors with making
        false statements of it production and sales that were
        glowing and artificially inflated the value of the stock.
        When the truth came to light, the complaint alleges the
        value of the stock collapsed, but before doing so
        insiders sold their shares and took $3,747,025 in illegl
        profits. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>DAKA INTERNATIONAL INC</strong>. -- On Oct.
        18,1996, a class action lawsuit was filed for purchasers
        of DADA stock between Oct. 30, 1995 and Sept. 9, 1996.
        The complaint charges DAKA and its CEO violated U.S.
        securities laws by falsely claiming that it was a rapidly
        expanding company with rising sales and profitability but
        concealing from the investing public a serious downturn
        in its Fuddruckers restaurant business and as a result
        the value of DAKA stock was falsely inflated to $33 per
        share. The complaint alleges that when the truth was
        revealed the stock fell to $8-5/8 per share. <br>
        </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>DEAN WITTER REYNOLDS, INC.</strong> - Dean
        Witter has been named as a defendant in a California
        Superior Court class action filed September 10, 1996 for
        placing investors into extremely risky limited
        partnerships that invested $1.2 billion in commodities
        and currency futures beginning in the 1980s through the
        1990s. Dean Witter claimed the investments, in light of
        its expertise, were &quot;safe&quot; and would yield high
        rates of return, but never fully, adequately or properly
        explained to investors the actual risks of such
        investment instruments and never provided prospectuses
        describing in writing the nature of the actual risks. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>DIGITAL LINK CORPORATION</strong> -- On
        October 18, 1996, a class action was filed against
        Digital Link Corporation and certain officers and
        directors on behalf of the purchasers of Digital's common
        stock during the period September, 1994 to December,
        1995. Investors allege that false and misleading
        statements by company officials concerning its
        profitability raised an $8 stock to $34 and allowed
        insiders to sell 1,363,000 shares, reaping illegal
        profits of $25 million from innocent investors who did
        not know that key products were in fact failing and that
        the company's future profitability was very doubtful. The
        complaint alleges that when the investing public learned
        the truth the price of the stock returned to $8. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>DISCREET LOGIC, INC</strong>. - On Oct. 23,
        1996, a class action was filed on behalf of buyers of
        Discreet Logic stock during the period September 13, 1995
        to May 1, 1996 as a result of officers and directors and
        underwriters artificially inflating the value of
        Discreet's stock to over $30 per by claims concerning new
        products and promises of significant future earnings
        which permitted insider traders to sell 3.6 million
        shares of Discreet stock at $30.25 per share for illegal
        profits of $109 million. When the truth became public the
        price of the stock fell to $9 3/4 per share. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>DONNKENNY, INC</strong>. - On November 21,
        1996, a class action lawsuit was filed on behalf of
        buyers of the stock of Donnkenny, Inc. between February
        14, 1995 through November 15, 1996. The Complaint alleges
        that Donnkenny and certain of its officers made false
        representions concerning Donnkenny's operating condition
        and financial results, which led investors to believe
        that Donnkenny had achieved a historical 30% growth rate.
        The complaint alleges that the company's reported sales,
        net income, and earnings per share for its fiscal years
        ended December 3, 1994 and December 2, 1995, and for the
        first two quarters of fiscal 1996, ended March 2, 1996
        and June 1, 1996, were materially overstated. Donnkenny
        common stock has collapsed by more than 86%, from its
        recent high. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>FALCON CABLE</strong> - Falcon Unitholders
        have filed a class action complaint on behalf of Falcon
        Unit holders arising out of Falcon's request that
        Unitholders exchange their Unit certificates for $9.02
        per unit. The complaint alleges that the exchange is
        undervalued and unfair to the Unit holders. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>FRITZ COMPANIES, INC.</strong> - On Aug. 13,
        1996, a lawsuit was filed in the U.S. District Court for
        the Northern District of California by purchasers of the
        stock of Fritz Companies Inc. during the period Aug. 29,
        1995 through July 23, 1996. The complaint alleges that
        Fritz and certain officers are responsible for violation
        of U.S. federal securities laws by making false and
        misleading statements. On July 24, 1996 Fritz admitted
        that its prior public pronouncements statements were
        false and that it reported non-existent revenues on its
        financial statements of $11.5 million. On this
        announcement Fritz shares collapsed in value
        approximately 55% from $27.50 on July 23, 1996 to $12.25
        per share July 24, 1996. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>GLEANAYRE TECHNOLOGIES, INC.</strong> - On
        Nov. 4, 1996, a class action was filed on behalf of all
        shareholders buying the common stock of Glenayre
        Technologies Inc. between Jan. 4, 1996 and Sept. 13,
        1996, alleging that Glenayre falsely inflated the value
        of the companies stock by misrepresenting the financial
        prospects of the company and claiming a `firm backlog` of
        product orders. Total over evaulation is claimed to be in
        excess of $50 million. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>HOME LINK CORPORATION</strong> - On Nov. 6,
        1996, a class action lawsuit was filed in the United
        States District Court on behalf of all purchasers of the
        common stock of The Home Link Corporation between
        February 22, 1996 and June 10, 1996. The complaint
        alleges that certain officers published information
        concerning the future profitabilitly of the company based
        on superior products for which there was extremely strong
        demand and that these false statments artificially
        inflated the value of the company's stock. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>HOME LINK CORPORATION</strong> - On Dec. 10,
        1996, a class action was filed in the United States
        District Court on behalf of all buyers of Home Link
        Corp.'s common stock between May 1, 1996 through and June
        10, 1996 alleging that Home Link and two of its officers
        made false and misleading statements regarding Home
        Link's assets, financial statements, business prospects,
        and expected revenues and as a result the value of the
        stock was artificially inflated. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>IMP, INC.</strong> - On September 17, 1996,
        another shareholder class action, as a result of alleged
        misrepresentations and insider trading by corporate
        officers, was filed in Santa Clara County Superior Court
        on behalf of all purchasers of IMP stock between April
        24, 1996 and July 22, 1996. IMP had made claims that
        there was a strong demand for its electronic products,
        which would lead to high earnings in 1997. On this
        &quot;good news&quot; IMP's stock jumped from $7 per
        share to $23 in May 1996 and allowed insiders to sell
        1,196,200 shares of their IMP stock at artificially
        inflated prices. Insiders are alleged to have illegally
        taken $23.7 million from innocent investors. Once the
        insiders had &quot;capitalized&quot; on their
        misrepresentation and the truth became public
        information, the stock plummeted to $7 per share. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>IDENTIX INC</strong>. -- On October 14, 1996,
        a class action complaint was filed against Identix and
        certain officers on behalf of buyers of Identix, Inc.
        common stock during the period January 31, 1996 through
        Augugust 26, 1996. The lawsuit charges officers with
        making false and misleading statements which artificially
        inflated the price of the company's stock. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>MADGE N.V.</strong> - On August 14, 1996,
        shareholders of the common stock of MADGE N.V.filed suit
        against the company for acquiring subsidiaries utilizing
        fraudulently inflated stock and in falsely reporting
        sales during the period October 12, 1995 to June 13,
        1996. The stock rose from approximately $28 per share to
        $48 before plummeting upon disclosure of corporate
        manipulation of its true financial condition. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>MALVY TECHNOLOGIES </strong>- On October 31,
        1996 a class action was filed in the United States
        District Court on behalf of purchasers of Malvy
        Technologies, Inc. common stock between November 1, 1993
        through May 24, 1995. The Complaint alleges that Malvy
        and former officers artificially inflated the price of
        the stock during the Class Period by making false
        statements, including bribes to stock brokers to promote
        trading in the stock. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>MEDAPHIS CORPORATION</strong> - On August 21,
        1996, an investor's class action was filed in the United
        States District Court in Atlanta Division by purchasers
        of Medaphis Corporation common stock between March 14,
        1996 August 14, 1996 as a result of pronouncements made
        by company officials predicting increased earnings which
        created the false expectation that successes were
        sustainable and continuing. In addition the company
        employed questionable accounting procedures to inflate
        earnings. </p>
        <p><strong>MERCURY FINANCE </strong>- On January 30,
        1997, a class action lawsuit was filed in the United
        States District Court for the Northern District of
        Illinois on behalf of purchasers of the securities of
        Mercury Finance Company during the period January 29,
        1994 to January 29, 1997. The complaint alleges that
        plaintiffs materially overstated its accounting and
        financial statements throughout the Class Period.
        Subsequent cases have been filed with other class
        periods.</p>
        <p><strong>MICROTEST, INC. </strong>- On Sept. 17, 1996,
        a class action was filed for buyers of Microtest, Inc.
        common stock between April 13, 1995 and Jan. 17, 1996.
        The lawsuit charges Microtest officers with making false
        statements about Microtest's profitability and ability to
        continue to grow, which artificially inflated the
        company's stock. The complaint alleges that sales of
        stock by insiders resulted in approximately $10 million
        being taken in profits from innocent investors by
        insiders. When the truth became known the stock dropped
        in price from a high of $25 to $5. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>MICRO WAREHOUSE, INC.</strong> - On Oct. 1,
        1996, a class action on behalf the common stock buyers of
        Micro Warehouse between March 26, 1995 and Sept. 27, 1996
        wasa filed. On Sept. 30, 1996, the company reported to
        the public and the press that it was &quot;likely to
        restate its financial results for the 1994 and 1995
        fiscal years&quot; because of &quot;errors in its
        accounting procedures,&quot; resulting in an after-tax
        charge of approximately $18 million. As a result anyone
        who bought this stock between March 26, 1995 and
        September 27, 1996 paid an artificially inflated price. </p>
        <p><strong>MOSSIMO, INC.</strong> - On Jan. 24, 1997, a
        class action was filed in the California Superior Court
        for Orange County for purchasers of Missimo, Inc. common
        stock during the period February 22, 1996 to January 14,
        1997. The complaint alleges Misrepresentations, False
        Financial Statements and Insider Trading.</p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>OAK TECHNOLOGY</strong> - Oak Technology
        executives were quick to report to Wall Street analysts
        that their shipping department was working around the
        clock and anyone checking found it was true. But the
        product shipped had little relationship to Oak
        Technology's actual sales, according to a class action
        lawsuit filed in Santa Clara County Superior Court,
        because Oak was shipping products that company officials
        knew would be returned to the manufacturer. In the
        electronics industry shipping unwanted products is known
        as &quot;stuffing the distribution channel.&quot; The
        class action lawsuit filed in July, 1996 in Santa Clara
        County alleges that Oak executives illegally reaped more
        than $100 million in profits on Oak stock from everyone
        who acquired the common stock of Oak Technology between
        July 27, 1995 and May 22, 1996. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>PACIFIC SCIENTIFIC CO.</strong> - On Nov. 5,
        1996, a class action filed in the United States District
        Court against PSC and its chief executive officer, Edgar
        S. Brower, on behalf of all persons who purchased
        Pacific's 7 3/4 percent debentures [due June 15, 2003]
        between Oct. 3, 1994 through and including July 2, 1996.
        The complaint alleges that PSC and its officers made
        claims about the company's products, including a solium
        fluorescent light that were materially false and
        misleading which were admitted to be false in an
        announcement made on July 2, 1996, causing the debentures
        to plunge in value. </p>
        <p><strong>PACIFIC SCIENTIFIC CORP.</strong> - On Dec.
        13, 1996, a class action lawsuit was filed against
        Pacific Scientific in the United States District Court on
        behalf of all purchasers of the company' common stock
        between Sept. 27, 1994 through July 2, 1996 alleging that
        as a result of false and misleading statements regarding,
        among other things, Pacific Scientific's business
        prospects and expected revenues, the price of the
        company's stock was artificially inflated. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>PARACELSUS HEALTHCARE CORP. -- </strong>On
        October 11, 1996, a class action was filed by purchasers
        of Paracelsus stock during the period August 13, 1996 to
        October 9, 1996 alleging the issuance of false and
        misleading financial statements in connection with the
        acquisition of Champion Healthcare Corporation earlier in
        1996. On October 9, 1996, Paracelsus announced that its
        earnings would be &quot;substantially&quot; lower because
        of accounting and financial reporting practices and
        procedures, just two months after the acquisition of
        Champion for $168 million of Paracelsus stock. During the
        same time Pacacelus issued and sold $325 million in notes
        and sold $40 million of common stock. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>PARADIGM TECHNOLOGY</strong> - On August 13,
        1996, it was announced that a class action lawsuit had
        been filed against Paradigm Technology in San Jose,
        California for violation of state securities statutes. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>PERFORMANCE NUTRITION, INC. </strong>- A class
        action has been filed for holders of Performance
        Nutrition stock during March 8, 1994 through and
        September 4, 1996. The Complaint alleges that officers
        misrepresented the company's performance to the public
        and failed to report material information, including the
        embezzlement conviction of a senior officer and failing
        to use proper accounting procedures. As a result the
        firm's earnings for the nine months ending June 30, 1996,
        plus year were misstated, and that its stock price was
        artificially inflated. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>PHYSICIAN RELIANCE NETWORK, INC.</strong> - On
        Sept. 17, 1996, a class action was filed purchasers of
        Physician Reliance stock during Feb. 12, 1996 to July 11,
        1996, inclusive which claims that the company
        misrepresented and omitted material information
        concerning the Company's Medicare billing practices which
        misstated the Company's financial condition in addition
        to violating Medicare reimbursement laws. As a result the
        price of Physician Reliance stock was falsely inflated to
        $27 per share. Later the stock plummeted to $13. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>PROXIMA CORPORATION</strong> - Purchasers of
        Proxima Corporation (`Proxima`) common stock during the
        period July 26, 1994 to August 17, 1995 paid artificially
        inflated prices based on claims that the company had
        successfully developed and was introducing revolutionary
        desktop projectors which would generate high profits in
        1997, according to the complaint filed on August 19,
        1996. In addition the company claimed that its new
        microlaser was moving toward profitability as planned.
        Neither was the case according to allegations in the
        complaint due to major shortages of key materials and
        critical components. The end result was that stock that
        sold at nearly $37 dropped to $18 and then to $13.50.
        But,before the bottom fell out, corporate insiders
        unloaded 700,000 shares to unsuspecting investors,
        pension funds and retirement funds at $37 a share,
        pocketing $19,000,000 which, should the allegations of
        the complaint be proven, be repaid to unsuspecting
        buyers. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>QUANTUM CORPORATION</strong> - On August 28,
        1996, Quantum Corporation and several officers were named
        in a class action in Santa Clara County Superior Court
        alleging misrepresentations concerning customer demand
        for a new line of disk drives and insider trading during
        the period Feb. 26, 1996 to June 13, 1996. Later Quantum
        admitted that demand for its new drives was substantially
        below expectations and resulting price cutting would
        necessarily have a negative effect on profits, which
        caused Quantum's stock to collapse in value. But before a
        drop in value of one-third of the stock's price, insiders
        sold 265,543 shares of their Quantum stock at inflated
        prices, several of Quantum's insiders sold <br>
        nearly all of their stock and insiders took an estimated
        $6.5 million in illegal trading &quot;profits&quot; from
        the pockets of innocent investors who did not have access
        to inside information. </p>
        <p><strong>QUARTERDECK CORPORATION</strong> - On Dec. 3,
        1996, a class action was filed in California Superior
        Court on behalf of purchasers of Quarterdeck Corporation
        common stock between January 26, 1996 to June 13, 1996
        alleging the company issued materially false and
        misleading statements about its products, revenues and
        profits which artificially inflated the price of
        Quarterdeck stock until the company reported sharply
        lower sales and a substantial operating loss for the
        third fiscal quarter ended June 30, 1996.</p>
        <p><strong>READ-RITE CORPORATION</strong> - On Dec. 12,
        1996, a class action lawsuit was filed in the California
        Superior Court on behalf of purchasers of Read-Rite
        Corporation common stockbetween April 19, 1995 to January
        22, 1996 alleging that Read-Rite falsely represented that
        it was enjoying strong demand for its products due to
        shortages for disk drive components, had competitive
        advantages due to its leadership position, was
        successfully developing new advanced thin film recording
        heads and would achieve high profit margins and expected
        sustained profitable growth of over $1 billion in 1996,
        which resulted in the company's stock being artificially
        inflated to $49-1/2 per share. The complaint states the
        company used $50 million of Read-Rite's cash to
        re-purchase two million of Read-Rite's own shares on the
        open market, allowing eight insiders to sell 815,000
        shares and pocketing over $26.4 million. In truth,
        Read-Rite's business was suffering from serious
        undisclosed adverse conditions, including difficulties
        developing its new products, softening demand,
        accumulation of excess inventories and erosion of its
        technological edge and competitive position. As a result
        of these problems, Read-Rite's stock fell sharply to
        $9-5/8 per share.</p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>RISCORP, INC</strong>. - On Dec. 4, 1996, a
        class action was filed in the United States District
        Court for the Middle District for buyers of Riscorp, Inc.
        common stock from February 28, 1996 through November 14,
        1996. The complaint alleges the company, a managed care
        worker's compensation insurance company, sold $190
        million dollars in stock to the public by falsifying the
        company's previous financial performance and making false
        statements about Riscorp's earnings prospects and
        operations, including the growth in Riscorp's in-force
        premiums, without revealing that some officers had been
        sued for extortion, mail fraud and other violations of
        federal and state law and that earning expectations would
        be impossible to achieve. With these disclosures the
        price of the stock collapsed form $19 to about $4 per
        share. </p>
        <p><strong>RISCORP</strong> - On Jan. 22, 1997, a class
        action was filed in the United States District Court for
        the Middle District of Florida on behalf of purchasers of
        Riscorp Inc. Class A common stock between Feb. 28, 1996
        and March 16, 1996. The complaint alleges that Riscorp,
        certain of its officers and directors, and the
        underwriters of the IPO violated the Securities Act of
        1933 and the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 by issuing
        to the investing public false and misleading statements
        regarding, among other things, Riscorp's financial
        performance, revenue, and earnings growth and their
        impact on the company's future. The Complaint<br>
        further alleges that as a result of these
        misrepresentations and omissions Riscorp's Class A common
        stock was artificially inflated throughout the Class
        Period.</p>
        <p><strong>SOLV-EX CORP.</strong> - On October 4, 1996, a
        class action on behalf of shareholders was filed in the
        United States District Court for the Southern District of
        New York allegeing that those who purchased the company
        stock between Feb. 15, 1995 and Sept. 30, 1996 paid
        inflated prices as a result of officers of the
        corporation misrepresenting the business, technologies,
        reserves, business prospects and value of Solv-Ex and by
        failing to make full disclosure of pertinent facts
        concerning the companies sales and prospects. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>STRATOSPHERE CORPORATION</strong> - On August
        16, 1996, an investor's class action was filed against
        Stratosphere Corporation and its officers with violations
        of law concerning misrepresentations made concerning
        current and future operations of the Stratosphere Tower
        Casino in Las Vegas which open in April of this year. The
        misrepresentations caused the stock to nearly double
        between December 1995 and April 1996 and allow insider
        traders to dump artificially inflated stock on innocent
        investors before the price crashed when the true facts
        were revealed, resulting in the stock price dropping to
        one-third of its December 1995 value. </p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>SUMMIT TECHNOLOGY, INC.</strong> - Summit
        Technology and certain officers were sued by stockholders
        in a class action on August 29, 1996 for insider trading
        and illegally taking profits based on confidential
        information which was purposely not divulge to the market
        and concealed from the Securities and Exchange
        Commission. During the period that Summit falsely
        inflated the value of its stock, the complaint alleges,
        it made a public offering and received proceeds of more
        than $100 million. Anyone who bought Summit stock between
        March 31,1995 and July 3, 1996 has a claim that Summit's
        stock was inflated above its true value as a result of
        the alleged misconduct. </p>
        <p><strong>SUNGLASS HUT INTERNATIONAL, INC.</strong> - On
        Jan. 23, 1997, a class action lawsuit was filed in the
        United States District Court for the Southern District of
        Florida on behalf of purchasers of Sunglass Hut
        International, Inc. between March 21, 1996 and Oct. 10,
        1996. The complaint alleges that defendants made
        materially false and misleading public statements which
        caused the stock price to rise to a high of $32.50 per
        share. The complaint further alleges that while problems
        were concealed from the investing public, certain
        officers and directors of the company sold over $5
        million worth of their Sunglass Hut stock holdingsat or
        near its highest price during the Class Period.</p>
        <p><strong>SYMANTEC</strong> - A new lawsuit against
        Symantec was filed in Santa Clara County Superior Court
        on August 9, 1996. Three investors allege that false and
        misleading statements by Symantec pushed the stock to $33
        1/4 in November, 1995, a new high, and it was this
        inflated value that allowed the company to buy a
        communications company, Delrina Inc. The investors also
        claim that Symantec insiders sold approximately 390,000
        shares of Symantec stock at artificially inflated prices,
        reaped a profit at the expense of innocent investors and
        abused their position of trust in violation of the U.S.
        securities laws. &nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>SYMANTEC CORPORATION</strong> - On March 18,
        1996, a class action complaint was filed in the
        California Superior Court for Santa Clara County ON
        behalf of purchasers of Symantec Corporation common stock
        during the period June 9, 1995 to January 8, 1996. The
        complaint alleges that defendants engaged in a fraudulent
        scheme, conspiracy and course of business that operated
        as a fraud or deceit on all persons who purchased or
        otherwise acquired Symantec stock. Further, the complaint
        alleges that Symantec's financial statements for its
        first and second quarters of fiscal 1996 were false and
        misleading in violation of Generally Accepted Accounting
        Principles.</p>
        <p>&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>TCSI CORPORATION </strong>- On Nov. 4, 1996, a
        class action was filed in the California Superior Court
        on behalf of shareholders purchasing TCSI Corporation
        common stock during the period October 11, 1995 to
        September 25, 1996. The complaint alleges that TCSI
        insiders and inflated TCSI's stock to a high of $29-3/4
        per share by claiming that TCSI was enjoying very strong
        demand for its products and that substantiala profits
        were expected throughout 1996 and 1997. The complaint
        alleges that insiders sold approximately six million
        shares of TCSI stock to the public at artificially
        inflated prices reaping alleged illegal profits of $105
        million. In March 1996, TCSI completed a public offering
        of TCSI stock in which TCSI and its founder and long time
        Chairman, Harvey E. Wagner, sold 1.5 million and 3.675
        million shares of TCSI stock. OVerall Wagner has sold 81%
        of his TCSI holdings and other officers sold 100% of
        their holdings. TCSI recently announced expected losses
        in 1996 and its stock collagpsed by more than 80 percent
        to $5.75 per share.&nbsp; </p>
        <p><strong>TELETEK INC</strong>. - On Dec. 2, 1996, a
        class action lawsuit was filed in the U.S. District Court
        for the District of Nevada on behalf of purchasers of the
        common stock of Teletek Inc. during the period between
        Nov. 22, 1993 and Nov. 7, 1996. The complaint alleges
        fraud, deceit and misrepresentation based on defendants'
        false representations of the company's financial and
        business conditions and that defendants participated in
        illegal insider trading as well as a scheme to
        artificially inflate and maintain stock prices by bribing
        stock brokers and promoters with stock and cash.</p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><strong>U.S. DIAGNOSTIC, INC.</strong> - A class
        action lawsuit was filed in the United States District
        Court for the Southern District of Florida on behalf all
        persons who purchased or otherwise acquired the
        securities of U.S. Diagnostic Inc. between March 15, 1996
        and December 23, 1996. The complaint alleges failure to
        disclose the nature of its relationships with Keith
        Greenberg, who has previously pleaded guilty to crimes
        relating to fraud, and certain persons affiliated with
        Greenberg.</p>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p><strong>VSI ENTERPRISES</strong> - A class action was
        filed against VSI Enterprises in the United States
        District Court for the Northern District of Georgia, on
        behalf of persons or entities who purchased shares of VSI
        Enterprises, Inc. common stock (i) on the open market
        from Oct. 6, 1995 through Jan. 8, 1996; or (ii) through
        the exercise of VSI Class B Warrants from Oct. 6, 1995
        through Dec. 18, 1995, when the Warrants were redeemed.
        The complaint alleges that VSI and its chief executive
        officer violated the federal securities laws, including
        Section 10(b) of the Securities Act of 1934, by
        misrepresenting and/or omitting material information
        concerning VSI's expected revenues and profits for the
        fourth quarter and year ended Dec. 31, 1995.</p>
