</h2>
<h2>Litigating Preemption Issues After <em>Medtronic v. Lohr</em></h2>
<p><strong>By Brian Wolfman &amp; Allison Zieve</strong> <br>
Public Citizen Litigation Group<br>
Copyright 1996, Public Citizen, Inc. </p>
<hr>
<p><strong>Table of Contents </strong></p>
<p><strong>I.	</strong><a href="#Introduction"><strong>Introduction</strong></a><strong>	</strong></p>
<p><strong>II. </strong><a href="#Brief"><strong>A Brief Overview of the Medical Device Amendments</strong>	</a></p>
<p><strong>III.	</strong><a href="#Decision"><strong>The Decision</strong></a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>A.<a href="#Opinion">	The Opinion of the Court</a></p>
<p>B.	<a href="#Breyer">Justice Breyer&#146;s Concurrence	</a></p>
<p>C.	<a href="#Dissent">The Concurrence in Part and Dissent in Part	</a></p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>IV.	</strong><a href="#Applying"><strong>Applying the</strong><em><strong> Medtronic</strong></em><strong> Analysis To Medical Device Cases</strong></a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>A.	<a href="#Products">510 (k) &quot;Substantial Equivalence&quot; Products	</a></p>
<p>B.	<a href="#Investigational">Investigational Devices	</a></p>
<p>C.	<a href="#Market">Pre-Market Approval Devices</a></p>
<p>D.	<a href="#Action">Other Causes of Action	</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>1. <a href="#Warranty">Breach of Express Warranty	</a></p>
<p>2. <a href="#Fraud">Fraud	</a></p>
</blockquote>
<p>E. <a href="#Compliance">Non-Compliance Claims	</a></p>
<p>F.	<a href="#Preempted">What May Be Preempted Under <em>Medtronic</em>?	</a></p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>V.	</strong><a href="#Statutes"><strong>Other Statutes</strong>	</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>A.	<a href="#Rodent">Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act	</a></p>
<p>B.	<a href="#Hazardous ">Federal Hazardous Substance Act	</a></p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>VI.	</strong><a href="#Conclusion"><strong>Conclusion	</strong></a></p>
<hr>
<p><strong>I. </strong><a name="Introduction"><strong>Introduction</strong></a></p>
<p>Since the early 1990&#146;s, defendants have been regularly arguing, and federal courts have been 
regularly holding, that the express preemption provision of the 1976 Medical Device Amendments 
(&quot;MDA&quot;) to the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act preempts damages actions brought by injured 
consumers against medical device manufacturers. The MDA&#146;s preemption provision, 21 U.S.C. 
360k(a), states that certain federal &quot;requirements&quot; that are &quot;applicable&quot; to medical devices 
preempt certain &quot;requirements&quot; that states maintain &quot;with respect to&quot; medical devices.</p>
<p>In its June 26, 1996 decision in <em>Medtronic v. Lohr</em>, the Supreme Court firmly repudiated the 
broad preemption rulings of the lower federal courts. The case involved injuries caused by a 
<em>Medtronic</em> pacemaker and its related components, including the lead, which is a wire connected 
to the pacemaker that delivers the electrical impulse to the heart. Specifically, the Court held that 
all three of Lora Lohr&#146;s claims&#151;based on defective design, defective manufacture, and failure to 
warn&#151;were not preempted by the MDA. <em>Medtronic</em> represents a wide-ranging victory for 
injured consumers. The Court&#146;s ruling, however, is a complex one and requires careful study. We 
believe that when <em>Medtronic</em> is properly applied, the courts will hold that few, if any, product 
liability claims are preempted.</p>
<p>The purpose of this article is to present our views on the meaning and application of the 
<em>Medtronic</em> decision. To fully appreciate MDA preemption arguments, however, it is necessary to 
understand how MDA regulation operates. In Part II below, we describe the MDA&#146;s regulatory 
structure in general, but a full explanation is outside the scope of this article. We direct the reader 
to the statute and regulations, the <em>Medtronic</em> opinion, which discusses the MDA in some detail, 
and lower federal court opinions, particularly the Eleventh Circuit&#146;s opinion in <em>Medtronic</em>.</p>
<p>In Part III below, we briefly summarize the decision in <em>Medtronic</em>. Obviously, anyone responding 
to a post-<em>Medtronic</em> preemption argument must study the opinions in detail.</p>
<p>Then, in Part IV, we apply the <em>Medtronic</em> decision to various types of product liability claims 
concerning different types of devices. We conclude that virtually all claims can proceed and that 
<em>no</em> cases will be preempted in their entirety. There is, however, work to be done in assuring that 
future medical device cases escape the preemption defense. Our optimism in the aftermath of 
<em>Medtronic</em> assumes a full understanding of the decision and its proper application.</p>
<p>Finally, in Part V, we discuss <em>Medtronic</em>&#146;s application to preemption provisions in other federal 
regulatory statutes that are similar, although not identical, to the MDA&#146;s preemption provision. In 
particular, we consider how <em>Medtronic</em> will affect preemption of damages actions under the 
Federal Hazardous Substances Act and the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act. 
Over the past few years, the lower federal courts have held that, like the MDA, these statutes 
broadly preempt personal-injury claims. In our view, these decisions are difficult to square with 
<em>Medtronic</em>, and we offer suggestions on litigating future FHSA and FIFRA cases.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>II. </strong><a name="Brief"><strong>A Brief Overview of the Medical Device Amendments</strong></a></p>
<p>For present purposes, there are three important facts about MDA regulation. <em>First</em>, each medical 
device falls into one of three classes. In theory, as the potential risks from the device increase, so 
does regulatory scrutiny under the MDA. Class I devices, such as band aids, are the least risky 
and are subject only to &quot;general controls&quot; applicable to all devices, such as general labeling 
requirements and good manufacturing practices rules promulgated by the Food and Drug 
Administration (&quot;FDA&quot;), the agency charged by Congress with implementing the MDA. Class II 
devices are more likely to cause harm if they are defective or misused, and thus the FDA may 
subject them to &quot;special controls,&quot; such as a specific labeling requirement. For instance, Class II 
tampons must carry a specific warning label required by the FDA. The vast majority of Class II 
devices, however, are not subject to any special controls.</p>
<p>Finally, Class III devices&#151;such as heart valves or the pacemaker leads at issue in 
<em>Medtronic</em>&#151;are those that, in theory, cannot be marketed until the FDA has found, after 
reviewing clinical data, that the device presents a reasonable assurance of safety and effectiveness. 
This process is known as pre-market approval (&quot;PMA&quot;). However, there is an important 
exception to PMA for Class III devices: the &quot;substantial equivalence&quot; exception. If a Class III 
device is &quot;substantially equivalent&quot; to a device marketed before the MDA&#146;s 1976 effective date, 
or to a device that itself was found to be substantially equivalent to a pre-1976 device, that device 
need not obtain PMA unless and until the FDA issues a regulation requiring PMA for that type of 
device. Products that enter the market based on &quot;substantial equivalence&quot; are known as 510(k) 
devices, after the section of the Act under which claims of substantial equivalence are made. Most 
Class III devices enter the market via section 510(k), and thus escape PMA, because the FDA 
has not issued the required PMA regulation. (Class I and II devices also enter the market 
pursuant to section 510(k), but by definition are not subject to PMA).</p>
<p><em>Second</em>, in rare instances, the FDA has issued device-specific requirements for particular types of 
devices. For instance, in addition to the tampon warning label mentioned above, the FDA has 
required that hearing aids bear certain labels, and that tampon absorbency be tested in a certain 
manner.</p>
<p><em>Third</em>, the FDA has issued regulations concerning the scope of preemption under 21 U.S.C. 
360k(a). These regulations, which construe the MDA&#146;s preemptive effect quite narrowly, are 
discussed in considerable detail in the <em>Medtronic</em> decision. They should be carefully consulted in 
every case where an MDA preemption defense is raised.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="Decision"><strong>III. The Decision</strong></a></p>
<p>Justice Stevens&#146; opinion is the opinion of the Court with respect to Parts I, II, III, the critical Part 
V, and Part VII. With respect to these Parts, the opinion is binding on all of the Nation&#146;s federal 
and state courts. Three other Justices joined the entire opinion including Parts IV and VI. Justice 
Breyer concurred in the judgment in full and joined in Parts I, II, III, V, and VII. The remaining 
four Justices concurred in part and dissented in part, in an opinion by Justice O&#146;Connor.</p>
<blockquote>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="Opinion"><strong>A. The Opinion of the Court</strong></a></p>
<p>Three holdings contained in Justice Stevens&#146; opinion are 
unanimous. (1) The Court unanimously rejected <em>Medtronic</em>&#146;s 
position that the MDA preempts all common-law claims against 
manufacturers for damages caused by medical devices. (2) The 
Court unanimously ruled that design-defect claims involving 
section 510(k) devices are not preempted. (3) The Court 
unanimously ruled that claims based on a manufacturer&#146;s failure to 
comply with duties &quot;equal to, or substantially identical to, 
requirements&quot; imposed under the MDA or FDA regulations are 
not preempted.</p>
<p>The opinion of the Court, on behalf of five Justices, further held 
that the Lohrs&#146; manufacturing and labeling claims were not 
preempted, even if they did more than merely seek to enforce the 
federal requirements. Justice Stevens&#146; opinion looked to both the 
statutory language and FDA regulations and noted the 
&quot;overarching concern that pre-emption occur only where a 
particular state requirement threatens to interfere with a specific 
federal interest.&quot; The statute and regulations, the Court held, 
&quot;require a careful comparison between the allegedly pre-empting 
federal requirement and the allegedly pre-empted state 
requirement to determine whether they fall within the intended 
pre-emptive scope of the statute and regulations.&quot;</p>
<p>The generality of the good manufacturing requirements and the 
labeling requirements applicable to <em>Medtronic</em>&#146;s pacemaker lead, 
the Court held, militated against a finding of preemption. Those 
federal requirements, the Court said, reflect &quot;important but entirely 
generic concerns about device regulation generally, not the sort of 
concerns regarding a specific device or field of device regulation 
which the statute or regulations were designed to protect from 
potentially contradictory state requirements.&quot;</p>
<p>Similarly, in probably the most significant passage in the entire 
opinion, the Court noted that the common-law claims at issue rely 
upon general state-law duties that are not directed specifically to 
medical devices. Thus, the Court found, the general duties to use 
due care in manufacturing and to warn users of potential risks 
pose no threat to federal requirements and are not the type of 
requirements that Congress or the FDA feared would impede 
FDA&#146;s ability to enforce specific federal laws and regulations. 
Because of their generality, such state-law claims are outside the 
prohibited category of requirements &quot;with respect to&quot; specific 
devices, within the meaning of section 360k(a).</p>
<p>Only three Justices&#151;Justices Kennedy, Souter, and 
Ginsburg&#151;joined Parts IV and VI of Justice Stevens&#146; opinion. In 
Part IV, Justice Stevens looked to the MDA&#146;s language and 
legislative history to conclude that section 360k(a) was not 
intended to preempt most, let alone all, damages actions. The 
statutory language and legislative history, Justice Stevens noted, 
distinguish the MDA from the statute at issue in <em>Cipollone v. 
Liggett Group</em>, Inc., 505 U.S. 504 (1992). In Part VI, the 
four-justice plurality stated that it need not decide whether a 
damages action could ever be a preempted &quot;requirement&quot; within 
the meaning of section 360k(a). The Justices reasoned that, since 
none of the Lohrs&#146; claims was preempted, a decision on that issue 
was not necessary. Moreover, because both the state and federal 
requirements would have to be highly specific before preemption 
could occur under section 360k(a) and the FDA&#146;s preemption 
regulations, it appeared that few, if any, common-law duties 
would ever be preempted. And, even in a case where the Court 
might find a damages claim preempted by the MDA, it might not 
need to resolve the express preemption question if the claim 
would also be preempted under conflict preemption principles.</p>
<p><a name="Breyer"><strong>B. Justice Breyer&#146;s Concurrence</strong></a></p>
<p>Justice Breyer concurred entirely in the judgment, as set forth in 
Justice Stevens&#146; opinion. He wrote separately to state his view 
that the reference to state-law &quot;requirements&quot; in section 360k(a) 
<em>does</em> encompass state-law damages suits, an issue as to which he 
agreed with the dissent.</p>
<p>Justice Breyer agreed with the principal opinion that none of the 
Lohrs&#146; claims was preempted, joining fully in that part of the 
opinion that analyzed each cause of action and found none of 
them preempted by the MDA. He stated that the applicable FDA 
requirements concerning the Lohrs&#146; claims were not &quot;specific&quot; in 
any relevant sense and that the FDA, as expressed in the 
agency&#146;s preemption regulation, 21 C.F.R. section 808.1(d), did 
not intend general, non-specific requirements to be preemptive. 
He noted that the language of section 360k(a) reflected basic 
principles of conflict preemption, but found no conflict between 
any federal requirement and any of the Lohrs&#146; claims. He further 
found no indication that &quot;Congress or the FDA intended the 
relevant FDA regulations to occupy entirely any relevant field.&quot;</p>
<p>Justice Breyer explained that he did not join in Part IV of the 
Court&#146;s opinion because he thought it unnecessary to the 
disposition of the case. He did not join in Part VI because he was 
not convinced that MDA preemption of common-law claims 
would be &quot;rare.&quot;</p>
<p><a name="Dissent"><strong>C. The Concurrence in Part and Dissent in Part</strong></a></p>
<p>Justice O&#146;Connor concurred in part and dissented in part. Her 
opinion was joined by Chief Justice Rehnquist and Justices Scalia 
and Thomas. She stated that common-law claims can constitute 
&quot;requirements&quot; within the meaning of section 360k(a), and she 
rejected the notion that there need be any specificity of either the 
federal preempting requirement or the state preempted 
requirement. Although concurring with the majority that the Lohrs&#146; 
design-defect claim was not preempted by the MDA, she stated 
that the Lohrs&#146; manufacturing-defect and failure-to-warn claims 
should be preempted to the extent they seek to impose 
requirements that are different from or additional to those 
imposed by the FDA&#146;s general good manufacturing and labeling 
rules. But she agreed with the majority&#146;s position that the Lohrs&#146; 
manufacturing-defect and failure-to-warn claims were not 
preempted to the extent that they allege violations of federal 
requirements.</p>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<p><a name="Applying"><strong>IV. Applying the </strong><em><strong>Medtronic</strong></em><strong> Amalysis to Medical Device Cases</strong></a></p>
<p>In light of the <em>Medtronic</em> decision, we now analyze MDA preemption by considering devices 
marketed at different levels of MDA regulation and by reviewing different types of product liability 
claims.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="Products"><strong>A. 510(k) &quot;Substantial Equivalence&quot; Products </strong></a></p>
<p><em>Medtronic</em> involved a 510(k) product which arrived on the market based on the 
manufacturer&#146;s claim of substantial equivalence to a pre-MDA device. In Part V 
of its opinion, the Court held that <em>none</em> of the standard product liability causes of 
action&#151;design defect, manufacturing defect, and failure to warn&#151;were 
preempted by the MDA. Justice Breyer fully joined this portion of the opinion, 
and noted in his concurrence that the same result was also required by conflict 
preemption principles. Thus, section 360k(a) does not preempt <em>any</em> claims 
regarding 510(k) products. The ruling applies to the vast majority of devices 
currently on the market&#151;all Class I and Class II devices (such as tampons), and 
most Class III devices, including silicone gel-filled breast implants, most 
pacemakers and their component parts, penile implants, and most other prosthetic 
and implantable devices.</p>
<p><a name="Investigational"><strong>B. Investigational Devices</strong></a></p>
<p>Some devices are marketed under an Investigational Device Exemption 
(&quot;IDE&quot;)&#151;a sort of FDA-approved experiment which allows an unapproved 
device to be used in humans in order to collect data. The manufacturer is 
exempted from typical pre-market approval obligations and other MDA demands 
during the term of the IDE. As the FDA puts it, an IDE &quot;permits a device that 
otherwise would be required to comply with a performance standard or to have 
pre-market approval&quot; to be used &quot;for the purpose of conducting investigations of 
that device.&quot; A few circuit courts prior to <em>Medtronic</em> had found preemption in 
cases involving an IDE. Those courts held that, although an IDE imposes no 
specific substantive obligations on a manufacturer, its<em> procedural</em> demands (e.g., 
applying for an IDE, collecting the data under FDA procedures) had preemptive 
effect.</p>
<p>This analysis&#151;to the extent that it was ever justified&#151;was swept away by 
<em>Medtronic</em> for several reasons. <em>First</em>, the IDE process imposes no significant 
substantive requirements on the design, manufacture, or labeling of medical 
devices. Both Part V of the Court&#146;s opinion and Justice Breyer&#146;s concurrence 
make clear that a high degree of substantive regulation on the same subject matter 
as the state-law duty relied upon is necessary before preemption can occur. To 
use the example given in Justice Breyer&#146;s concurrence, even a federal rule as 
specific as one requiring that hearing aids use a 2-inch wire would not preempt 
state rules about the packaging or shipping of hearing aids. Thus, as applied to a 
state design-defect claim, for example, if the 510(k) process, which at least 
makes the demand of product equivalence, does not preempt (as the Court held), 
then the IDE process, which does not make even that demand, surely does not 
have preemptive effect. So, too, with other standard product liability causes of 
actions, such as those involved in <em>Medtronic</em>, under which IDE products are 
subject to <em>less </em>substantive regulation than other MDA-regulated products.</p>
<p><em>Second</em>, the reliance on FDA regulations concerning the scope of preemption 
both by the Court majority and Justice Breyer is relevant in the IDE context. 
Under 21 C.F.R. 50.20, the informed consent form that the patient must sign 
before using an IDE device &quot;may [not] include any exculpatory language through 
which the subject ... is made to waive or appear to waive&quot; the manufacturer&#146;s 
liability for negligence. While not an interpretation of the MDA&#146;s preemption 
provision, section 50.20 is a gap-filling interpretation of the MDA, which makes 
clear that the IDE process was not intended to obliterate state damages remedies. 
Since the Court majority deferred to the FDA&#146;s views on preemption of state law, 
the similar concern toward state-law remedies expressed in section 50.20 should 
carry considerable weight in the IDE context.</p>
<p><em>Third</em>, consistent with our understanding of <em>Medtronic</em>&#146;s effect on future IDE 
cases, on the Monday after <em>Medtronic</em> was handed down, the Supreme Court 
granted certiorari in a Sixth Circuit case which had held that the IDE process 
preempted the plaintiff&#146;s claims, vacated the Sixth Circuit&#146;s ruling, and remanded 
for reconsideration in light of <em>Medtronic</em>. Particularly when juxtaposed with the 
Court&#146;s other rulings on pending MDA preemption cases issued the same day, the 
Court&#146;s action in the Sixth Circuit case is very favorable.</p>
<p><em>Finally</em>, as discussed in more detail in Part IV.E. below, even if the IDE 
regulations did impose substantive requirements that could have preemptive effect, 
a plaintiff would be free, under state law, to sue to enforce the IDE requirements. 
All nine justices agreed that damages suits seeking to enforce federal requirements 
are not preempted.</p>
<p><a name="Market"><strong>C. Pre-Market Approval Devices</strong></a></p>
<p>Although <em>Medtronic</em> did not involve a device that had gone through PMA, we 
believe that Justice Stevens&#146; majority opinion requires that preemption be rejected 
in such circumstances. In addition, rulings issued by the Supreme Court a few 
days after the decision in <em>Medtronic</em> strongly support this position.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>1. As noted earlier, the position of the Court majority, as 
expressed particularly in Part V of the opinion, is that preemption 
requires a high degree of specificity and substantive overlap with 
regard to both the potentially preemptive federal requirement and 
the potentially preempted state law. On the federal side, just as 
the majority noted with respect to the 510(k) process, the FDA 
does &quot;not &#146;require&#146; [a PMA device] to take any particular form 
for any particular reason.&quot; The PMA process, while more 
scientifically rigorous than 510(k), applies to devices <em>generally</em>: it 
demands that all PMA devices have a &quot;reasonable assurance&quot; of 
safety and effectiveness, but it does not &quot;require&quot;&#151;to use the 
language of section 360k(a)&#151;any <em>specific </em>design, manufacturing 
process, or labeling. Thus, as the majority put it in referring to 
FDA labeling and manufacturing rules, there is no &quot;specific 
mandate on manufacturers or producers&quot; in the PMA rules. This 
position is well stated in the Solicitor General&#146;s <em>amicus</em> brief in 
Medtronic in a discussion of Ms. Lohr&#146;s design-defect claim:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Neither the FDCA nor the FDA&#146;s regulations 
prescribe criteria for the design of devices. The 
design of a device originates with its 
manufacturer.... [Design] specifications are 
applicable to a device as a result of a voluntary 
decision of a private party, the manufacturer, to 
introduce the device into the market with a design 
of the manufacturer&#146;s choosing. That federal law 
attaches a consequence to such private decisions 
does not convert them into federal &quot;requirements.&quot; 
Cf. <em>American Airlines, Inc. v. Wolens</em>, 115 S. 
Ct. [817, 824 (1995)].</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Further, the final paragraph of Part V of the Court&#146;s opinion is 
highly significant. That paragraph shows that, for preemption to 
occur, a great deal of specificity is required on the state-law side 
of the preemption equation&#151;a specificity generally absent from 
state damages suits. Because of the importance of this paragraph, 
we quote it in full:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Similarly, the general state common-law 
requirements in this case were not specifically 
developed &#146;with respect to&#146; medical devices. 
Accordingly, they are not the kinds of 
requirements that Congress and the FDA feared 
would impede the ability of federal regulators to 
implement and enforce specific federal 
requirements. The legal duty that is the predicate 
for the Lohrs&#146; negligent manufacturing claim is the 
general duty of every manufacturer to use due 
care to avoid foreseeable dangers in its products. 
Similarly, the predicate for the failure to warn 
claim is the general duty to inform users and 
purchasers of potentially dangerous items of the 
risks involved in their use. These general 
obligations are no more a threat to federal 
requirements than would be a state-law duty to 
comply with local fire prevention regulations and 
zoning codes, or to use due care in the training 
and supervision of a workforce. These state 
requirements therefore escape pre-emption, not 
because the source of the duty is a judge-made 
common-law rule, but rather because their 
generality leaves them outside the category of 
requirements that &#167;360k envisioned to be &quot;with 
respect to&quot; specific devices such as pacemakers. 
As a result, none of the Lohrs&#146; claims based on 
allegedly defective manufacturing or labeling are 
pre-empted by the MDA.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Having already disposed of the design-defect claim on the ground 
that section 510(k) has no preemptive effect, the above-quoted 
paragraph dealt only with the manufacturing and duty-to-warn 
claims. However, its rationale&#151;that the state-law duties are 
general duties to use due care or to inform&#151;applies fully to a 
claim of defective design concerning both PMA and non-PMA 
products. Indeed, under the common law of Florida (where the 
Lohrs&#146; claims arose), the scopes of the duties in design-defect 
and manufacturing-defect cases are identical. Thus, the fact that a 
device has received PMA should not, under <em>Medtronic</em>, bar any 
of the standard product liability causes of action.</p>
<p>Justice Breyer&#146;s concurrence adds force to this analysis. In his 
view, the FDA has the power to determine, within the broad 
statutory mandate, which kinds of federal law have preemptive 
effect, and the FDA did not intend the requirements applicable in 
<em>Medtronic</em>&#151;which are at the same level of generality as those 
applicable in the PMA context&#151;to have preemptive effect. It is 
worth noting, too, that at least as to the design-defect claim, 
nothing in Justice O&#146;Connor&#146;s dissent demands a conclusion of 
preemption in PMA cases.</p>
<p>Moreover, PMA products are subject to the very same labeling 
and good manufacturing practice rules that the Court in 
<em>Medtronic</em> found did not preempt Ms. Lohr&#146;s garden-variety 
manufacturing-defect and failure-to-warn claims. Thus, such 
claims are not preempted in the PMA context. Although the FDA 
reviews and passes on the proposed labeling when it considers a 
PMA application, the same general substantive &quot;requirements&quot; 
apply to the labels of all MDA products. Moreover, the Court, in 
the portion of its opinion holding that claims of non-compliance 
with federal law are not preempted, pointed out that an FDA 
regulation permits manufacturers of PMA devices to make certain 
labeling, quality control, and manufacturing changes to enhance 
product safety <em>without prior FDA approval</em>. In light of that 
regulation, damage claims regarding a failure to warn would not 
generally be &quot;different from, or in addition to&quot; the federal 
requirement within the meaning of section 360k(a).</p>
<p>Finally, it bears emphasis that, although not specifically addressed 
in the <em>Medtronic</em> opinion, a claim that a manufacturer should have 
warned by means other than the product label would not be 
preempted under either <em>Medtronic</em> or the reasoning of the 
Court&#146;s earlier decision in <em>Cipollone</em>. Part V of the Opinion 
requires an overlap between the specific federal rules at issue and 
the theory of the state-law duty at issue. Justice Breyer&#146;s 
concurrence also strongly suggests this point, by explaining that a 
federal rule on one aspect of hearing aid regulation would not 
preempt state-law on another aspect of hearing aid regulation. 
And in his <em>amicus</em> brief filed in <em>Medtronic</em>, the Solicitor General, 
relying on <em>Cipollone</em>, specifically stated that a non-label-related 
failure-to-warn claim would not be preempted. </p>
<p>2. On the Monday following the <em>Medtronic</em> decision, the Court 
disposed of numerous certiorari petitions in MDA preemption 
cases that had accumulated while <em>Medtronic</em> was pending. These 
actions were very significant. In each of the cases involving a 
510(k) device, where the lower court had held that some or all of 
the plaintiff&#146;s claims were preempted, the Supreme Court granted 
the petition, vacated the decision below, and remanded for 
reconsideration in light of its <em>Medtronic</em> decision. In addition, the 
Supreme Court granted, vacated, and remanded a Seventh 
Circuit PMA case involving injuries allegedly suffered from 
collagen injections, where the court of appeals had affirmed 
dismissal of the entire case on preemption grounds. However, in a 
second PMA collagen case, in which the Ninth Circuit had held 
that no common-law claims are ever preempted by the 
MDA&#151;<em>and in that case only</em>&#151;the Court simply denied 
certiorari, leaving the Ninth Circuit&#146;s no-preemption precedent in 
place.</p>
<p>To grant, vacate, and remand a petition, the Court must have the 
votes of five justices. Therefore, the disposition of the Ninth 
Circuit PMA case indicates that the Court did not have the vote 
of Justice Breyer to remand that case, but did have his vote to 
remand the Seventh Circuit PMA case. This outcome further 
confirms our reading of Part V of the Court&#146;s opinion and the 
effect of Justice Breyer&#146;s joinder in it. While, ordinarily, the denial 
(or even the grant) of certiorari does not have precedential effect, 
granting, vacating, and remanding a case constitutes a ruling on 
the merits of a case. The combined effect of the opinion in 
<em>Medtronic</em> and of the Court&#146;s actions on the various pending 
petitions leaves little doubt that standard product-liability claims 
with respect to PMA devices are not preempted.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a name="Action"><strong>D. Other Causes of Action</strong></a></p>
<p>While claims of defective design and manufacture and failure to warn, pled under 
negligence and/or strict liability theories, are the standard product liability claims, 
other claims are also regularly pled in medical devices case. We address the two 
most common types&#151;breach of express warranty and fraud.</p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="Warranty"><strong>1. Breach of Express Warranty</strong></a></p>
<p>Under <em>Cipollone</em>, breach of express warranty claims are not 
preempted because they are grounded in a contractual duty 
between the parties, not in an independent obligation imposed by 
state law. Whether or not expressed on the product label, such 
claims (e.g., that the product has a lower failure rate than do the 
competitors&#146; products), thus are not preempted because they do 
not impose state-law &quot;requirements.&quot; <em>Medtronic</em> reaffirms and 
deepens this understanding. There are no FDA &quot;requirements&quot; 
concerning promises that a medical device manufacturer may or 
may <em>not</em> make, other than that it may not generally claim that its 
product has received FDA approval. Certainly, no FDA 
requirement concerning manufacturers&#146; warranties contains the 
degree of specificity demanded by the <em>Medtronic</em> opinion. 
Moreover, a state-law breach of warranty claim is not preempted 
because it falls squarely within the Court&#146;s discussion of &quot;general 
state ... requirements [that] were not specifically developed &#145;with 
respect to&#146; medical devices....&quot; Accordingly, breach of warranty 
&quot;requirements ... escape pre-emption, not because the source of 
the duty is a judge-made common-law rule, but rather because 
their generality leaves them outside the category of requirements 
that &#167; 360k envisioned to be &#145;with respect to&#146; specific devices....&quot; 
Indeed, as the Court pointed out, the FDA&#146;s preemption 
regulations specifically note that warranty claims under the 
Uniform Commercial Code are requirements of &quot;general 
applicability&quot; that are not preempted by section 360k(a).</p>
<p><a name="Fraud"><strong>2. Fraud</strong></a></p>
<p>State-law fraud claims are not preempted for much the same 
reasons that express warranty claims are not preempted. They are 
claims of general applicability grounded not in any specific 
requirement that a device be made in particular manner, but, as 
<em>Cipollone</em> teaches, in a general duty not to deceive. A claim, for 
instance, that a plaintiff&#146;s doctor was misled into prescribing a 
certain medical device has nothing to do with whether the product 
is defective. In fact, in finding no preemption of the labeling and 
manufacturing claims in <em>Medtronic</em>, the Court relied on 
<em>Cipollone&#146;s</em> holding that the fraud claims there were not 
preempted because, while they dealt in some sense with the 
preempted field of &quot;smoking and health,&quot; they were grounded in 
the more general common-law duty not to deceive.</p>
<p>Furthermore, neither the MDA nor any regulations promulgated 
thereunder contain general anti-fraud provisions with which a 
state-law fraud claim could conflict, and thus a fraud claim would 
clearly survive under <em>Medtronic</em>&#146;s requirement that specific 
federal requirements be in place for preemption to occur. If the 
federal requirements for labeling and good manufacturing 
practices were too general to have preemptive effect in 
<em>Medtronic</em>, then surely a manufacturer&#146;s even more general duty 
to be truthful in its dealings with the FDA has no preemptive effect 
under the MDA.</p>
<p>The ability to prosecute fraud claims in the aftermath of 
<em>Medtronic</em> survives regardless of whether the claims are pled in 
their traditional common-law form or under a modern consumer 
protection statute prohibiting unfair and deceptive acts and 
practices. Indeed, the FDA&#146;s preemption regulations, relied on by 
the Court, specifically note that state unfair trade practices 
requirements are not preempted by the MDA.</p>
<p>Fraud allegations in medical device personal-injury cases have 
often taken two distinct forms and have been analyzed separately 
in some MDA preemption cases. <em>First</em>, plaintiffs have alleged that 
they and their doctors have been defrauded into using a product 
that they would not have used had the manufacturer not deceived 
them. With respect to that claim, the foregoing analysis applies.</p>
<p><em>Second</em>, plaintiffs have claimed&#151;particularly in collagen and 
Bjork-Shiley heart valve cases&#151;that the manufacturer defrauded 
the FDA into granting PMA for a particular product or into taking 
or failing to take some other regulatory action. Usually the claim is 
based on both affirmative misrepresentations to the agency and on 
the withholding of pertinent safety information from the agency. 
This type of claim&#151;although focused on the manufacturer&#146;s 
conduct toward the FDA rather than toward the public or medical 
professionals&#151;is still grounded in the general duty not to deceive 
and, thus, is not preempted under <em>Medtronic</em> and <em>Cipollone</em>. 
And even though the claim may, in some cases, demand an 
inquiry into the FDA&#146;s processes, no preemption-triggering 
federal <em>requirement</em> would be at issue in pursuing a state-law 
fraud-on-the-FDA claim. Prior to <em>Medtronic</em>, several courts had 
held that section 360k(a) preempted a fraud-on-the-FDA claim 
on the ground that it was up to the FDA, not state law, to police 
such fraud. Those holdings cannot withstand the holding in 
<em>Medtronic</em>, because, as noted earlier, they simply cannot be 
squared with the preemption provision and its implementing 
regulations, which say nothing about exclusive FDA authority and 
require the existence of specific federal <em>requirements</em> before 
preemption can occur. Moreover, as discussed in more detail 
below, preemption of fraud-on-the-FDA claims is inconsistent 
with the views of all nine Justices that state-law claims premised 
on non-compliance with federal law are not preempted. Thus, 
even if some federal <em>requirement</em> were relevant to the 
fraud-on-the-FDA cause of action, preemption could be defeated 
wherever the plaintiff claimed that, as a result of the fraud, FDA 
standards for product approval or any other relevant standard 
had not been met. For instance, the plaintiff could allege that the 
general requirement that manufacturers be truthful with the FDA in 
its labeling was violated, giving rise to liability under state law.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a name="Compliance"><strong>E. Non-Compliance Claims</strong></a></p>
<p>In <em>Medtronic</em>, the plaintiffs&#146; back-up position with regard to the 
manufacturing-defect and failure-to-warn claims was that, even if the general FDA 
rules regarding manufacturing and labeling had preemptive effect, a claim of 
negligence or strict liability premised on violations of those general FDA rules did 
not establish a requirement &quot;different from, or in addition to&quot; any federal 
requirement, but rather a requirement that was the same as the federal 
requirement. The majority opinion and the dissent agreed, concluding that tort 
claims alleging violation of federal rules or standards are not preempted by section 
360k(a).</p>
<p>Although the plaintiffs in <em>Medtronic</em> did not make a non-compliance argument 
with regard to their design-defect claim (there being no federal design standards), 
the Court&#146;s opinion (as well as the dissent) would allow claims seeking to enforce 
all existing federal MDA standards, such as that for misbranding. Indeed, for 
years state regulatory agencies have enforced federal device standards in many 
areas, and the FDA has encouraged those agencies to do so.</p>
<p>It should be kept in mind that a non-compliance claim arises under state law and 
is <em>not</em> a cause of action under the FDCA. The lower federal courts are in 
agreement that there is no implied right of action under the FDCA, and it is 
unlikely that this view will change. The proper allegation is that the manufacturer 
was negligent (or violated other state-law principles embodied in a statute or the 
common law) in failing to abide by federal device standards. Although it is 
probably not necessary to allege violation of federal standards in the complaint, 
<em>no one should risk being bounced from court for failing to plead the case 
properly</em>. Therefore, to be safe, and assuming one has the facts, the complaint 
should allege that the defendant violated state law (<em>e.g.</em>, was negligent or the like) 
for failing to abide by FDCA standards. For a failure-to-warn type claim, the 
general federal labeling standards can be alleged. For a manufacturing-defect 
claim, discovery may or may not be necessary before violation of individual good 
manufacturing practice rules can be alleged. However, even there the standards 
are so general that allegations will often be possible at the inception of the case. If 
the case is ultimately tried partially or entirely on a non-compliance basis, jury 
instructions will have to track the general federal standards, as well as the general 
liability standards under state law.</p>
<p><a name="Preempted"><strong>F. What May Be Preempted Under </strong><em><strong>Medtronic</strong></em><strong>?</strong></a></p>
<p>Justice Breyer did not join Parts IV and VII of Justice Stevens&#146; opinion, which 
therefore speak only for a four-Justice plurality. Justice Breyer expressed his view 
that the language of section 360k(a) encompasses preemption of damages claims 
(which the plurality strongly questioned), but only when there is considerable 
specificity in, and subject-matter overlap between, state and federal device 
requirements. As an example of where preemption would occur, he described a 
hypothetical case in which a plaintiff claimed that a manufacturer was negligent for 
failing to use a one-inch wire in a hearing aid, when the FDA <em>required</em> a two-inch 
wire. This result, although not a part of the opinion of the Court, when combined 
with the analysis of the four dissenters, appears to represent the view of five of the 
justices. Few state-law claims take the highly particularized form suggested by 
Justice Breyer, and few FDA requirements operate at that level of specificity.</p>
<p>Nevertheless, his analysis may require a finding of preemption in a few instances. 
For example, a duty-to-warn claim in a case involving a tampon, where the 
manufacturer gave the FDA-mandated warning, might be preempted, if the 
state-law claim was that the warning should have been different from that which 
the FDA requires. Even there, however, an analysis of whether FDA rules <em>forbid</em> 
manufacturers from adding to the label might be warranted, and, of course, 
non-label-related claims&#151;such as defective tampon design&#151;would not be 
preempted. And, as noted earlier, a failure-to-warn claim premised on a 
manufacturer&#146;s duty to warn by means other than the label should not be 
preempted under <em>Cipollone</em>. Moreover, according to all nine Justices, a state-law 
claim that the manufacturer did not provide the federal warning would not be 
preempted.</p>
<p>Thus, while a quite limited universe of claims may be preempted by combining the 
Breyer and O&#146;Connor analyses, we want to emphasize that no opinion expressing 
the views of the <em>Court</em> held that common-law claims come within the reach of 
section 360k(a) and a four-Justice plurality strongly suggested that they do not. 
Therefore, as MDA preemption cases move forward, we suggest that plaintiffs be 
prepared to press the view that section 360k(a) does not reach damages actions. 
In many if not all cases, fully briefing this issue may not be necessary, since the 
claims will not be preempted under the majority opinion in any event. Thus, the 
plaintiff may only want to mention the point briefly, but with clarity, so as to 
preserve the issue. There are two reasons for doing so. <em>First</em>, while adding up the 
views of the justices expressed in two separate opinions may reveal a good deal 
about the individual thinking of the current justices, the result does not represent a 
precedent of the Court. The plurality view expressed in Parts IV and VI of Justice 
Stevens&#146; opinion may ultimately be seen as more persuasive in the lower courts. 
<em>Second</em>, the no-preemption view should be argued because if and when another 
MDA preemption case is before the Supreme Court, the composition of the 
Court may have changed, providing an opportunity for plaintiffs to expand the 
four-Justice plurality.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a name="Statutes"><strong>V. OTHER STATUTES</strong></a></p>
<p>Other federal statutes contain preemption provisions, and the preemption defense has become a 
favorite of defendants in personal-injury and property-damage cases involving a wide range of 
products. Below, we focus on preemption under the Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and 
Rodenticide Act (&quot;FIFRA&quot;) and the Federal Hazardous Substances Act (&quot;FHSA&quot;) because the 
defendants&#146; preemption arguments have been particularly effective in connection with those 
statutes. Much of our analysis, however, may be relevant to other statutes containing similar 
express preemption provisions. </p>
<blockquote>
<p><a name="Rodent"><strong>A. Federal Insecticide, Fungicide, and Rodenticide Act</strong></a></p>
<p>FIFRA&#146;s preemption section provides that:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>[States] shall not impose or continue in effect any requirements for 
labeling or packaging in addition to or different from those 
required under this subchapter.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Defendants have had considerable success in using this provision to avoid liability 
for damage caused to crops and land by pesticides. In fact, a majority of the 
federal circuit courts, as well as a number of state supreme courts, have found 
broad preemption of damages claims under FIFRA. In the future, however, 
several aspects of the <em>Medtronic</em> decision will be of particular help in defeating 
FIFRA preemption defenses.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>1. <em>Medtronic</em> held that state requirements &quot;equal, or substantially 
identical&quot; to federal requirements were not preempted under the 
MDA, which, similar to FIFRA, preempts requirements &quot;different 
from or in addition to&quot; federal requirements. Thus, putting aside 
the question whether a damages remedy constitutes a 
&quot;requirement&quot; within the meaning of FIFRA&#146;s preemption 
provision, where a state-law damages claim alleges failure to 
comply with federal requirements, that claim is not preempted.</p>
<p>In FIFRA cases, this holding may be particularly useful for two 
reasons. <em>First</em>, the key language of FIFRA&#146;s preemption 
provision, referring to &quot;requirements&quot; that are &quot;in addition to, or 
different from&quot; federal requirements, is very similar to the language 
in section 360k(a) of the MDA.</p>
<p><em>Second</em>, like many MDA requirements, the requirements of 
FIFRA are general and ongoing. For example, if a pesticide 
manufacturer knows or should know of an environmental risk 
posed by its product, the manufacturer is required to revise its 
labeling to reflect that risk. Thus, if a plaintiff claims that his or her 
land was damaged by a pesticide and that the risk of damage 
should have been disclosed on the product&#146;s label, the complaint 
should allege that the defendant negligently failed under state law 
to comply with duties imposed under FIFRA. In many cases, the 
common-law duties on which the plaintiff&#146;s allegations are based 
will mimic the defendant&#146;s duties under FIFRA, which places the 
burden of product testing, identification of product risks, and 
hazard labeling on the manufacturer.</p>
<p>2. Looking to the general language of section 360k(a) of the 
MDA and the generality of the FDA&#146;s regulations, <em>Medtronic</em> 
identified an &quot;over-arching concern that pre-emption occur only 
where a particular state requirement threatens to interfere with a 
specific federal interest.&quot; Thus, in considering the plaintiffs&#146; 
defective manufacturing and failure-to-warn claims, the Supreme 
Court made &quot;a careful comparison between the allegedly 
pre-empting federal requirement and the allegedly pre-empted 
state requirement to determine whether they fall within the 
intended pre-emptive scope of the statute and regulations.&quot; The 
Court concluded that the relevant federal requirements&#151;the FDA 
good manufacturing practices and general labeling 
rules&#151;reflected important but altogether generic concerns, not 
specific concerns which the statute or regulations were designed 
to protect from potentially contradictory state requirements. 
Similarly, the general common-law duties at issue in <em>Medtronic</em> 
were not specifically developed with respect to medical devices, 
and thus, the Court held, are not the kind of requirements that 
Congress or the FDA feared might impede the FDA&#146;s 
implementation and enforcement of the MDA.</p>
<p>Like the good manufacturing requirements and general labeling 
requirements of the MDA, FIFRA&#146;s labeling requirements are 
general. The Act&#146;s misbranding provisions require manufacturers 
to draft labeling to warn about their products&#146; principal dangers 
and to alter and supplement labeling after a product receives 
marketing approval. And in contrast to the statutorily prescribed 
warnings of the Public Health Cigarette Smoking Act of 1969 at 
issue in <em>Cipollone</em>, pesticide registrants are obliged under FIFRA 
to update their labels to protect against adverse environmental 
effects.</p>
<p>Thus, in staving off a preemption defense in cases involving 
products regulated under FIFRA, it will be important to 
emphasize the generality of FIFRA&#146;s labeling requirements and 
the flexibility that FIFRA and the EPA give to manufacturers to 
draft labeling. FIFRA&#146;s preemption provision applies only to 
labeling and packaging and thus preemption of common-law 
claims should be relevant, if at all, only with regard to a claim that 
the defendant failed to warn about a product&#146;s hazards. However, 
some courts have recast various other claims as failure-to-warn 
claims when considering FIFRA preemption. Therefore, 
application of <em>Medtronic</em>&#146;s analysis may be useful in preserving 
not only failure to warn claims, but also claims of negligent testing, 
defective design, and the like.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a name="Hazardous "><strong>B. Federal Hazardous Substance Act</strong></a></p>
<p>The FHSA, which is enforced by the Consumer Product Safety Commission 
(&quot;CPSC&quot;), applies to thousands of products, ranging from toys to paint remover. 
The FHSA contains two preemption provisions, but in reported cases defendants 
have focussed on only one, section 18(b). Section 18(b), which is in some ways 
similar to the MDA&#146;s section 360k(a), provides:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>[I]f a hazardous substance or its packaging is subject to a 
cautionary labeling requirement under [the Act] designed to 
protect against a risk of illness or injury associated with the 
substance, no State or political subdivision of a State may 
establish or continue in effect a cautionary labeling requirement 
applicable to such substance or packaging and designed to 
protect against the same risk of illness or injury unless such 
cautionary labeling requirement is identical to the labeling 
requirement under [the Act].</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Although defendants have had substantial success in avoiding liability under this 
provision, <em>Medtronic</em> may alter this trend. As noted earlier, <em>Medtronic</em> deferred 
to the FDA's regulations narrowly interpreting the preemptive scope of the statute. 
This aspect of the decision is highly relevant in the FHSA context because the 
CPSC has promulgated preemption regulations that strongly suggest that <em>only</em> 
state statutes, regulations, and other positive laws are within the preemptive scope 
of the FHSA. Moreover, when the CPSC's preemption regulations were 
proposed, manufacturers specifically asked the CPSC to include common-law 
rules in its definition of the types of state requirements subject to preemption. In 
promulgating its final rule, the CPSC rejected the manufacturers' request on the 
ground that the statute did not provide for preemption of state-law damages 
actions. Under <em>Medtronic</em>, this interpretation of the statute by the expert agency 
should receive deference. </p>
<p>As discussed above, <em>Medtronic</em> held that state requirements &quot;equal, or 
substantially identical&quot; to federal requirements are not preempted under the MDA. 
Applying this holding to the FHSA, and again putting aside the question whether a 
damages remedy constitutes a &quot;requirement&quot; under the FHSA&#146;s preemption 
provision, a state-law damages claim alleging failure to comply with an FHSA 
cautionary labeling requirement is not preempted, since the Act expressly saves 
from preemption &quot;identical&quot; state requirements.</p>
<p>In addition, like FIFRA&#146;s preemption provision, section 18(b) applies only to<em> 
labeling</em> requirements. Moreover, many courts have stated that FHSA&#146;s 
preemption provision is effectively identical to FIFRA&#146;s. Accordingly, the above 
discussion of FIFRA can be applied in large part to FHSA cases. For instance, 
like labeling regulations under the MDA and FIFRA, FHSA&#146;s labeling rules are 
general and leave manufacturers significant freedom. Labels must include any 
language required by CPSC, and they must also include &quot;an affirmative statement 
of the principal hazard or hazards&quot; and &quot;precautionary measures&quot; for avoiding 
hazards. Labels may also include any other material, as long as that material does 
not negate or disclaim any federally required statement. Manufacturers do not 
even submit labeling to the CPSC for review, much less approval.</p>
<p>Thus, in pleading a failure-to-warn claim in a hazardous substance case, or in 
defending against a motion for summary judgment based on preemption, it will be 
important to emphasize the generality of FHSA&#146;s labeling requirements and the 
freedom accorded to manufacturers to design their own labels. Applying the 
<em>Medtronic</em> analysis, a manufacturer&#146;s duty to warn about hazards under the 
FHSA is substantially identical to the common-law duty to warn.</p>
<p>Finally, <em>Medtronic</em> held that the MDA did not preempt the Lohrs&#146; design-defect 
claim because no federal requirement regulated the <em>design</em> of the medical device 
at issue. To use the example given by Justice Breyer in his concurrence, a specific 
design requirement for the length of a hearing aid wire would not preempt claims 
based on state-law requirements for hearing aids that were unrelated to the 
wire-length requirement. In the context of FHSA, <em>Medtronic</em>&#146;s insistence on 
subject-matter congruence between the state and federal requirements means 
that, even where a federal cautionary labeling requirement is in place in connection 
with one product hazard, state-law claims alleging a failure to warn about a 
different hazard would not be preempted.</p>
<p>For example, if a specific CPSC requirement mandates that the label of products 
containing a particular chemical disclose a risk of poisoning if the product is 
ingested, a claim alleging failure to warn about the risk of toxicity through 
inhalation of that product should not be preempted because that claim would not 
create any risk of conflict with the federal requirement regarding the ingestion risk. 
Even before <em>Medtronic</em>, some decisions applied such an analysis because the 
FHSA&#146;s preemption provision preempts only state cautionary labeling 
requirements designed to protect against the same risk of illness or injury as the 
federal cautionary labeling requirement. <em>Medtronic</em> affirms the reasoning of those 
cases.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a name="Conclusion"><strong>VI. CONCLUSION</strong></a></p>
<p><em>Medtronic v. Lohr</em> represents a substantial victory for medical device consumers. With perhaps a 
few exceptions, <em>Medtronic</em> lifts the burden of the preemption defense from tort plaintiffs in 
personal-injury cases involving medical devices. In addition, <em>Medtronic</em>&#146;s reasoning should prove 
useful to plaintiffs seeking to defeat preemption defenses in cases involving products regulated 
under other federal laws.</p>
<p>Dated: July 24, 1996<br>
Copyright 1996, Public Citizen, Inc. </p>
<hr>
