<h2>CONSUMER FRAUD: Spotting and Protecting Yourself 
Against It [A General Primer] </h2>
<h4>By Richard Alexander, Esq. Editor </h4>
<hr><p><font size=-1>
San Jose, California attorney Richard Alexander, a National Honor Scholar at The Law School, University of Chicago, was certified as a civil trial advocate by the National Board of Trial Advocacy in 1980, has been specially recognized as a Trial Lawyer by the California Trial Lawyers Association, is a former member of the Board of Governors of The State Bar of California, currently serves as Vice President of Consumer Attorneys of California and is a founding member of the National Association of Consumer Advocates. He is the founder of <a href="http://www.alexanderlaw.com">The Alexander Law Firm</a> [http://www.alexanderlaw.com], a medium size law firm specializing in individual and class action litigation arising from negligence, toxic chemical, defective product, mass accident, environmental and fraud cases on behalf of consumers and small businesses. The firm holds Martindale-Hubbell's highest rating and is recognized in the List of Preeminent Law Firms in the United States. The firm sponsors <a href=http://consumerlawpage.com>The Consumer Law Page</a> [http://consumerlawpage.com] on the World Wide Web. Copyright Richard Alexander 1996.</font></p>
<hr>

<p><strong>Contents</strong></p>
<div align=center><center>
<table cellpadding=5 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
<tr><td valign=top><a href="investment.shtml"><font size=4>I</font><font size=2>NVESTMENT</font></a><font size=2> </font><ul>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Bank Examiner &amp; Pigeon Drop Schemes</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Business Opportunities</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Credit Card Scams</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Get-Rich-Quick (Pyramid) Schemes</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Home Equity Loans</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Investment Scams</font></font></li>
</ul>
</td><td valign=top width=50%><a href="health.shtml"><font size=4>H</font><font size=2>EALTH </font></a><ul>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Health &amp; Fitness Clubs</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Long-term Care Insurance</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Medical Quackery</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Weight Loss </font></font></li>
</ul>
</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top width=50%><a href="automobiles.shtml"><font size=4>A</font><font size=2>UTOMOBILES</font></a><ul>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Car Repairs</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Lemon Law</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Odometer Rollback </font></font></li>
</ul>
</td><td valign=top width=50%><a href="home.shtml"><font size=4>H</font><font size=2>OUSING AND HOME</font><font size=1> </font></a><ul>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Charitable Solicitations</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Home Repair Fraud</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Landlord-Tenant Law</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Lien - Law</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Warranties</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Door-to-Door Sales</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Telemarketing Fraud </font></font></li>
</ul>
</td></tr>
<tr><td valign=top width=50%><a href="entertainment.shtml"><font size=4>E</font><font size=2>NTERTAINMENT</font></a><font size=2> </font><ul>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Contest Cons</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Magazine Subscriptions</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Travel Scams</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Shopping</font></font></li>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Vacation Timesharing </font></font></li>
</ul>
</td><td valign=top width=50%><a href="consumer_action.shtml"><font size=4>C</font><font size=2>ONSUMER ACTION</font></a><ul>
<li><font color="#408080"><font size=2>Taking Charge When You Are Treated Unfairly. </font></font></li>
<li><a href="../complain.shtml"><font color="#408080"><font size=2>How To Resolve Your Consumer Complaint: 
Self-Help or Class Action? </font></font></a></li>
</ul>
</td></tr>
</table>
</center></div>
<p><font size=5>A</font>CKNOWLEDGMENT and <font size=5>I</font>MPORTANT <font size=5>W</font>ARNING </p>
<p>The Attorney General of Missouri and the General's consumer protection staff were the impetus for 
this article, which in large part has adopted an outstanding brochure on consumer fraud prepared for 
citizens of Missouri. Because of this valuable contribution to consumer education The Consumer 
Law Page salutes the Missouri AG in its leadership on this issue. </p>
<p>Unfortunately consumer fraud laws differ from state to state and for a California lawyer to attempt to 
set forth all the law as it varies from state to state is a monumental undertaking. We did not do that 
here. What is here is a general primer on consumer law scams and what you should protect yourself 
against. This article is a general statement of consumer law issues and obviously is not legal advice. 
That can only come from a lawyer admitted to practice in your state, after you have explained to him 
or her all the facts concerning your particular legal issue. </p>
<p>For additional information on a wide range of consumer topics open The Consumer Law Page 
section entitled Brochures, where articles on automobiles, banking, credit, career, employment, 
funerals, general consumer, health &amp; medical, investing, loans, mortgages, products &amp; services and 
timeshares can be found. </p>
<p>Exercising and affirming consumer rights starts with you, providing you are informed and alert. </p>
<p>To learn the specific laws in your state on the issues discussed here, always check with your local 
city or county consumer agency administrator, legal aid office, state or country bar association, 
county prosecutor's office of consumer affairs or state Attorney General's office for the specific laws 
in your state on a particular issue. </p>
<hr>
