<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<!--looking find locate seeking search lawyer attorney litigation  law firm alexander richard , specializes handles does practices handles
consumer law tort class action(s) product liability defective products  toxic chemical(s)  fraud bodily injury personal injury pollution 
poison(s) environmental mass accident negligence aircrash, lives located resides practices california northern san jose nationally united states --><h2><a href="index.html#menu">The Alexander Law Firm:</a> RECORD OF ACHIEVEMENT</h2>
<hr>
<p>While it is often said that the &quot;past is prologue,&quot; a testimonial, endorsement or result in a particular case does not constitute a promise, prediction or guarantee 
regarding the outcome of any other case. For those whom we represent The Alexander Law Firm commits its best efforts. Those efforts over the years are reported 
here. Each case was dependent on a multiplicity of factors and unique facts. Because of many different factors, results always will differ from case to case. For that 
reason the results that we obtained in these cases are no guarantee that we can again achieve the same results in any future case. In fact to understand what we 
achieved in these cases we have provided a substantial amount of information, including references to news articles and court files, so anyone can evaluate and 
make their own determination of the result and our record. There is only common factor in all the cases reported here: the plaintiff was represented by Richard 
Alexander or The Alexander Law Firm.</p>
<hr>
<p><a href="#recent"><img src="t-dn.gif" alt="**" align=middle width=20 height=35></a> <a href="#recent">Recent Cases</a></p>
<hr>
<p>$8,132,000 jury verdict for plaintiffs in <i>Byer v. Market Transport</i> after an eight-day trial, tried by Richard Alexander <i>after rejecting a settlement offer of $4.5 
million</i>. Byer, age 15, suffered irreversible brain damage when the Byer family car was sideswiped by a tractor and trailer. The jury deliberated one day before 
delivering its unanimous verdict. Reported: California Jury Verdict Reporter, February 7, 1986; The Recorder, January 7, 1986, page one; San Francisco 
Examiner, December 21, 1985; San Jose Mercury News, December 21, 1985, B-1; Times Tribune, December 22, 1985, A-1. </p>
<p>Lead attorney in <i>Nevarez v. Foremost Dairies</i>, a multi-vehicle auto-truck collision that resulted in identical C- 5/C-6 quadriplegic injuries to a father and daughter, 
when their car was rear-ended on smoke-covered I-5 by the defendant's tractor and trailer. More than 25 depositions and motions were required to bring the case 
to trial in San Francisco. Following a five-day settlement conference, the defendant's insurance carriers offered $10,000,000 in settlement or promised they would 
try the case in response to my demand of $13,500,000. While trailing for a trial department in San Francisco, an additional $1,000,000. was forthcoming and the 
plaintiffs accepted a total settlement of $11,000,000. Reported in the California Jury Verdict Reporter, February 7, 1986. </p>
<p>Trial attorney for the plaintiff in <i>Aceves v. Regal Pale</i> <i>Brewing</i>, 24 C.3d 502, in which the California Supreme Court unanimously recognized the special risks 
presented to construction workers, confirmed the duty of their employer to take special precautions to prevent on-the-job injuries and reaffirmed a jury verdict for 
the plaintiff. </p>
<p>Lead attorney for Donald Coca, a passenger in a car stopped for a Vehicle Code violation, whose face was destroyed by a shotgun which had been placed on his 
shoulder by a San Jose Police Officer who was riding along with the California Highway Patrol. Cash settlement of $4,000,000 believed to be the highest dollar 
award in the history of the California Highway Patrol and the City of San Jose. Featured front page report, San Jose Mercury News, September 23, 1983; see also 
San Jose Mercury News, September 21, 1983, B-1, Peninsula Times Tribune, September 22, 1983. Featured evening news channels 2, 4, 5, 7, and 11. </p>
<p>Represented five families in wrongful death actions against PG&amp;E arising from a defectively designed scaffolding system in a 500' vertical shaft which failed at 
PG&amp;E's <i>Helm's Creek Hydroelectric Facility</i> in Fresno resulting in structured settlements providing in excess of $25 million to the surviving families. This case was 
the subject of the San Francisco Examiner, Sunday, May 16, 1982, page one headline story.</p>
<p>Lead attorney in <i>Throop v. Conrail</i>, an $8,500,000 award for triple amputation electrical burn injuries suffered by a teenager trespassing on railroad property. 
First lawyer in the United States to uncover and prove the railroad's electrical system had caused on average, 24 deaths/major injuries per year. Case featured by 
The Washington Post, page one, May 29, 1981, and The San Jose Mercury News, page one, May 28, 1981. AP and UPI national wire. In-depth feature, CBS 
Evening News, by Charles Osgood. </p>
<p>In <i>Treanor v. Eller Associates</i>, recovered $136,000 for Michael Treanor, a construction laborer, whose leg was broken when an unshored trench collapsed in 
Santa Cruz. The recovery against the owner-general contractor was based on the failure of Treanor's employer, a subcontractor, to take special precautions under 
the <i>Aceves v. Regal Pale</i> doctrine, even through Treanor was largely responsible for his injuries having been ordered by OSHA the previous week not to enter the 
trench. Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 84444. </p>
<p>Counsel for plaintiff in <i>Sinacore v. Superior Court</i>, 81 CA3d 223, a case of first impression in California, recognizing the confidentiality of a social worker's 
records of children. </p>
<p>Trial attorney for plaintiff in <i>Aiello v. Bank of America</i> <i>Realty,</i> for injuries suffered by a 35-year- old operating engineer. Before trial plaintiff offered to settle his 
claim for $45,000. The defendant responded by offering $7,500. The final judgment plus interest paid to Mr. Aiello after trial totaled $277,871. </p>
<p>Attorney for plaintiff in <i>Wagnon v. City of Los Gatos</i>, a $450,000 recovery for a motorcycle passenger who lost her arm due to a defective roadway. The arm 
was totally separated and following multiple surgeries re-attached. The motorcycle operator, who was uninsured, was found to be driving under the influence of 
alcohol, amphetamines and cocaine. See San Jose Mercury News, October 3, 1981, page B-1. </p>
<p>Counsel for plaintiff in <i>Buchanan v. Stanford University</i> in which a college freshman received severe cuts to his arm when he collided with a plate glass door 
during a dormitory water fight. Stanford was forced to admit that it replaced plate glass with safety glass <i>after</i> doors were broken, despite the knowledge that plate 
glass causes severe injury and indoor water fights were common. In settlement Stanford agreed to pay $140,000 plus provided the injured student with a fully paid 
four-year college education, including tuition, room and board, at any college or university of his choice. San Jose Mercury News, B-1, October 22, 1981. </p>
<p>Attorney for plaintiffs in <i>Sollfrank v. Mid-Cal Farms,</i> a $2.3 million recovery for the wrongful death of a husband and father caused by drunk driving. Page one, 
San Jose Mercury News, November 23, 1981. </p>
<p>Attorney for plaintiff in <i>Rockstroh v. National</i> <i>Semiconductor</i>, a $450,000 award for an electrician who momentarily forgot that the distribution panel he was 
working on was energized and touched the electrified gear with an uninsulated tool resulting in third-degree burns to 30% of his body. San Jose Mercury News, 
March 5, 1983. </p>
<p>Attorney for plaintiff in <i>Doe v. Jeske</i>, a $1,150,000 verdict for a twelve-year-old victim of child molestation. </p>
<p>As co-counsel for plaintiff in <i>Cunningham v. Shortstop</i>, quadrupled offer to plaintiff's attorney resulting in recovery of $1.5 million in cash, plus an annual annuity 
of $40,000 for a brain-damaged teenager injured by a teenage driver who was intoxicated by beer sold by defendant. First contacted six days before trial. At the 
initial pre-trial conference, defendants disclosed a pathologist would be testifying who had died nine months earlier along with two other experts. Retained those 
experts that evening and forced settlement on the third day of jury selection. </p>
<p><i>Franklin Beacham v. Park Cleaners</i>, San Luis Obispo County Superior Court Nos. 44097, 43194, 43120 and 42906, in which a natural gas explosion 
destroyed a card shop and beer bar in Paso Robles. Expert analysis of the natural gas pipe showed severe corrosion initiating from the outside surface due to water 
that contained a high concentration of sodium chloride and no sulfates, indicating it was not tap water. Global settlements with the bar, dry cleaner and others for 
approximately 12 plaintiffs in 1978. </p>
<p>Trial attorney in<i> Doherty v. Sides</i>, September, 1979, Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 408525 in which an unattended four year old child struck a playmate 
in the eye with sharp scissors and caused a six year old to lose sight in one eye. Settled second day of trial for $72,500 under parents homeowners' coverage. </p>
<p>Verdict for plaintiff of in <i>Koong v. Ehlert</i>, San Francisco Superior Court No. 722-173 , January 9, 1980, in a case of soft tissue injuries arising from an auto 
collision at Battery and Market Streets. </p>
<p>Verdict for plaintiff in <i>Donaldson v. Almaden Vineyards</i>, San Francisco Superior Court No. 705-265 after a six day trial before Judge Jack Ertola, January 23, 
1980 involving soft tissue injuries arising from an auto collision. </p>
<p><i>Claudine Brown and Caryl Meslo v. Ford Motor Company and British Leyland</i>, Santa Clara County March, 1980 before Judge DeMarco was a good case of 
liability against Leyland, but was lost at trial. Tried with James Boccardo. Full size Ford Galaxie, 500 series, rear-ended by TR6 which had a defective fuel line that 
gravity fed to the firewall and then was pumped around the front of the engine to the carburetor. The Ford was an established fire hazard as a result of the filler tube 
being secured to the tank with a rubber grommet and bolted to the fender, which when struck caused the filler tube to be pulled from the tank and gush gasoline. 
Terrible burns to two teenagers who are both lovely people. A case that should not have been lost. </p>
<p>Defense verdict in <i>Johnson v. Western Chain Saw</i>, Humboldt County No. 57559, in which plaintiff, an alcoholic lost his leg while cutting firewood with a chain 
saw. Case tried on the theory that the safety trigger was designed to collect sawdust and jam on full throttle. Tried May, 1980. </p>
<p>In <i>Gonzalez v. Western Pacific,</i> Alameda County Superior Court No. 473156-0, an FELA action, a railroad employee was killed when a defective plug door fell 
from a freezer car due to improper maintenance of the door rollers. Settled September, 1980. </p>
<p>$400,000 recovery for wrongful death in <i>Gasich v. P.G. &amp; E., </i>in which a bulldozer operator who was clearing a firetrail for Kaiser Permanente struck an 18 inch 
gas distribution line from which covering dirt had been eroded and suffered terminal burns. Settled September, 1981. Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 
433294 </p>
<p>Co-trial counsel with James Boccardo in <i>Dickens v. General Motors</i>, Provo, Utah, November, 1981, in which a GM dealership installed steering components 
incorrectly and caused a van to roll over killing a 19 year old. Defense verdict, but under unique Utah procedure the 100% Mormon jury evaluated the damages to 
the surviving mother at $400,000. </p>
<p>In <i>Beasley v. Sterling Homes</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 398242, filed April 12, 1978, the plaintiff, while reaching for a dropped bar of soap, 
slipped and fell through a glass shower enclosure reinforced with wire which broke into shards and caused her to lacerate the back of both legs and suffer 
permanent drop foot. Discovery revealed that wire reinforced safety glass should only be used in fire applications and shower enclosures should utilize tempered 
glass which breaks into many small pieces. Settled August, 1982. </p>
<p><i>Gonsalves v. Borba</i>, a wrongful death of a three year old, who died in an unlocked and illegal hot tub, on her first day at a day care center, demonstrates the 
callousness of some insurance carriers. The case settled as plaintiff's counsel walked into the jury room for policy limits of $100,000, which was accepted against 
the advice of counsel. Throughout the case the policy had been demanded, but not paid. At the settlement conference approximately $50,000 to $60,000 was 
offered to the parents. Father is an attorney in Modesto. Stanislaus County Superior Court No. 183484. Settled November, 1983. </p>
<p>Trial attorney for an employee of a roofing contractor in <i>Perry v. Western Refrigerating and Cold Storage</i>, a suit for injuries caused by a fall of 25 feet from a 
domed warehouse roof. Western Refrigerating, the building's owner, offered $16,000 in settlement before trial. Because of a $16,000 worker's compensation 
insurance lien, the offer would have resulted in no recovery for the plaintiff. The jury agreed with the plaintiff that the contemplated work by the contractor required 
the taking of special precautions by the owner to prevent falls. After an eight-day trial the jury awarded the plaintiff $285,000, less twenty-five percent for the 
plaintiff's comparative fault. </p>
<p>Trial attorney for an injured electrician in <i>Reeves v. M and</i> <i>T Corporation</i> who fell from a tar- covered ladder and injured his back. The suit against the property 
owner settled for $275,000 on the second day of trial. Marin County Superior Court No. 107183. </p>
<p>Attorney for the widow of a 44-year-old male nurse suffering from delirium tremens when arrested by the San Jose Police Department who died after the police 
taped a paper bag over his head. The final award in <i>Rushin v. City of San Jose</i> was ordered not to be disclosed. See San Jose Mercury News, April 30, 1981, 
page one, November 5, 1981, and December 15, 1982. </p>
<p>Represented numerous children who were victims of sexual assault. In one representative case, <i>Doe v. F.</i>, a confidential sealed file of the Santa Clara County 
Superior Court, a total settlement of $420,000 was paid by a child molester's homeowners insurance company for psychological injuries suffered by a minor. 
Although the insurance company originally denied coverage for the homeowner's criminal act, the settlement was obtained by proving the molester was &quot;negligent by 
reason of mental incapacity&quot;, an act covered by homeowner's insurance coverage. These unique cases were the subject of a front-page article in the San Jose News 
on June 23, 1983, and a feature article in the San Jose Mercury News on June 24, 1983. See also feature article, San Francisco Examiner, page 1, August 5, 
1984. </p>
<p>Co-counsel in a $1,500,000 total recovery for three high school students injured in a high-speed rollover of a Chrysler four- wheel-drive vehicle on a dirt road. 
<i>Ramacciotti, Cassin and MacKenzie v. Chrysler, Cesano Liquors. </i></p>
<p>Attorney for Julie Baker, 18-year-old victim of sexual abuse by her stepfather when she was age nine. Child molester forced to convey all his property, including 
one triplex, and two single family houses, to plaintiff in satisfaction of her claims for damages for emotional distress. Featured evening news Channels 2, 4, 5, 7, and 
11, January 17, 1984. San Jose Mercury News, January 17, 1984, page 1. San Francisco Chronicle, January 18, 1984, page one. Associated Press national wire. 
All ABC in California, including KABC, Los Angeles and Good Morning America, January 18, 1984. Face to Face, Sunday ABC San Jose, January 22, 1984. 
See also Oakland Tribune, B-1, February 24, 1984, San Francisco Examiner, page 1, Sunday, August 5, 1984, Los Angeles Times, Sunday, September 9, 1984, 
and San Jose Mercury News, November 20, 1984, for feature article on incest victims. </p>
<p>Trial attorney for a 27-year-old construction laborer employed by Pestana Construction Company who was injured by a backhoe during the installation of a sewer 
line for the Monterey Regional Water Pollution Control Agency. The total award for Robert Dante was $325,000, plus waiver of the worker's compensation lien. 
The lien was waived because of Pestana's negligence in ordering the plaintiff into a trench when heavy equipment was operating nearby. Morrison-Knudsen and 
MRWPCA both held liable under Restatement 416 requirements of <i>Aceves v. Regal Pale</i>. Salinas Californian, January 26, 1984. </p>
<p>Trial attorney for Michael Wilson, a construction laborer with Krzich Pipeline Engineering, who suffered burns while &quot;mudding&quot; the interior of storm drains. 
Extensive investigation revealed that natural gas lines had been damaged by another contractor, Bilardi Construction, several blocks away and had collected in the 
storm drain under construction by Krzich. The recovery in <i>Wilson v. PG&amp;E and</i> <i>Bilardi Construction</i> totaled $300,000. </p>
<p>Lead attorney for three ironworkers injured at PG&amp;E's Helm Creek Project, Fresno County, when a man hoist negligently maintained by Granite-Ball-Groves, 
slipped and fell in April 1981. <i>Burdette, Gillio and Drake v. PG&amp;E</i>. Total recoveries $245,000. </p>
<p>Trial attorney for the plaintiff in <i>Fannuchi v. Bettencourt,</i> Santa Rosa Superior Court, $325,000 recovery for a registered nurse rear-ended by a hay truck. </p>
<p>In <i>Valente v. Union Oil,</i> a construction laborer employed by Timec to perform routine repairs to Union Oil's Santa Maria Refinery was burned by steam escaping 
from a defective pipe fitting. Suit filed in San Luis Obispo Superior Court resulted in a settlement of $140,000 prior to trial. </p>
<p>Trial attorney in <i>McGreevy v. Abbott</i>, first civil child molestation case tried in Santa Clara County. The child molester claimed he accidentally brushed this 
six-year-old plaintiff's cheek and pled no contest in his criminal prosecution to save his family further embarrassment. The victim's therapist reported the child had 
substantially recovered during one year of therapy but may require further counselling during adolescence and adulthood. Rejecting a good faith settlement offer of 
$100,000, Farmers Insurance Company offered $40,000. Five-day trial resulted in a $175,000 verdict for the child and her mother. San Jose Mercury News, B-1, 
December 1984. </p>
<p>Obtained $750,000 recovery for burn injuries caused by a defectively designed electrical switch for PG&amp;E lineman who admitted causing his own injury. 
<i>Smethurst v. G&amp;W Specialty Company</i> settled the morning of trial after extensive pre- trial discovery against manufacturers of a 12,000 volt oil-filled switch 
which exploded when Smethurst turned the switch to the wrong position and, contrary to good practice, attempted to return the switch to its original position. 
Similar switches caused 10 deaths and 21 serious injuries over a 25-year period, but no warnings were ever distributed to users. Smethurst suffered burns over 
60% of his body and was disabled for 14 months before returning to work as a PG&amp;E lineman. San Francisco Chronicle, January 31, 1985; Times Tribune, A-1, 
January 31, 1985. </p>
<p>Chief counsel for plaintiffs in <i>Furchtenicht v. Peabody</i> <i>Barnes and General Electric</i>, a product liability case for wrongful death settled for $750,000. Plaintiffs' 
decedent, father of three, electrocuted himself when he clipped the grounding plug from an extension cord that was attached to a three-prong submersible sump 
pump. During a heavy downpour, Mr. Furchtenicht attempted to drain his swimming pool of ground water by using the submersible sump pump with the modified 
extension cord. The sump pump shorted as he stood next to it and he suffered cardiac arrest. Subsequent investigation showed the pump wiring had shorted due to 
defective insulation and the manufacturer's assembly protocols were designed to pass defective pumps, which all helped overcome the decedent's high level of 
contributory negligence (as an engineering student in college he had taken three courses in electricity). Unreported settlement paid by Gibraltar Casualty Company 
of Newark, New Jersey, Check 6562 of October 11, 1985, in the sum of $750,000. </p>
<p>Chief counsel for the victims of child molestation in <i>California Casualty v. Weber</i>, a case of first impression in Santa Clara County. Weber, a convicted pedophile, 
had molested two young girls, ages 8 and 9. After suit was filed he was advised to tender his defense to his homeowner's insurance company, which brought the 
instant action seeking to avoid defending Weber and not satisfying the children's claims. The court held that Weber suffered from a mental disease, could not control 
his conduct in accordance with reason and the insurance carrier, under these limited circumstances, was obligated to satisfy the victims' claims for damages, even 
though a result of criminal conduct. Decision rendered February 26, 1986, by Hon. Read Ambler. </p>
<p><i>Bucol v. City of Oakland</i> arose from the shooting death of an 18-year-old in the Oakland Auditorium at a Kool and The Gang Concert, by unknown assailants. 
Thorough investigation and discovery showed that the City and rock promoter failed to establish reasonable security precautions, despite knowing the reputation of 
the character of the crowd usually attracted by this type of concert and not stopping the concert when multiple fights and thefts were reported. Despite intervening 
criminal conduct, the rock promoter agreed to settle this tragic death for the sum of $250,000. </p>
<p>Chief trial counsel in the first jury trial in the United States contesting the power of cities to grant an exclusive monopoly to a cable television firm, <i>Pacific West 
Cable</i> <i>Company v. City of Sacramento</i>, U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of California. Called into case one month before trial. In four weeks, six feet 
of pleadings, 4,000 pages of deposition testimony, and more than 1,000 documents were digested and analyzed. Trial began March 23, 1987, and after thirteen 
weeks, the jury found that cable television was not a natural monopoly, that the construction of a cable television system did not cause significant disruption, noise, 
environmental or safety hazards, that the franchising process did not result in a better cable television system, that the franchising process was adopted to enhance 
the contributions and political power of local politicians, and that the granting of monopoly to disseminate news, information and entertainment was a violation of the 
constitutional right of free speech. Co-counsel Harold Farrow, Oakland. Reported, The Sacramento Bee, June 6, 1987, A-34. See also &quot;City Ends Cable TV 
Monopoly&quot;, Sacramento Bee, July 7, 1987; &quot;Cable Television Monopoly Voided&quot;, The Sacramento Union, July 7, 1987; Editorial: &quot;A Clear Signal on Cable TV&quot;, 
The Wall Street Journal, July 23, 1987; Editorial: &quot;Cabling the County&quot;. The Wall Street Journal, September 14, 1987. </p>
<p>Co-counsel for plaintiff in<i> Century Federal v. Cities of Palo Alto, Atherton and Menlo Park,</i> a federal civil rights action for denying free press rights by granting 
a monopoly to one cable television company. San Francisco Federal Judge Eugene Lynch ordered the defendant cities to allow construction of Century's cable 
system. Palo Alto Times Tribune, February 12, 1987, A-1; San Jose Mercury News, February 13, 1987, B-1. See also Wall Street Journal editorial, &quot;Cabling the 
Country&quot;, September 14, 1987. </p>
<p>$1,750,000 recovery in <i>Whiteley and Cox v. The State of California, </i>a personal injury action against the California Highway Patrol arising from a late night 
pursuit of an escapee from the California Youth Authority who was driving a stolen vehicle. Depositions of 21 experts were taken in this case. The central liability 
issue, which was strongly disputed, was whether the CHP had activated its siren to warn the general public that it was an emergency vehicle. The fleeing escapee 
violated a red light and collided with plaintiffs causing multiple fractures and head injuries. At the time of the settlement, two years post- injury, both plaintiffs were 
preparing to return to work. Settled June 19, 1989, Fresno County Superior Court, Action No. 376393-5. </p>
<p>In <i>Repetto v. Weyerhauser</i>, a vehicle was driven under a trailer parked across a commercial street in San Jose at night. The owner, Mr. Repetto, had a blood 
alcohol level of .18 and had a suspended license at the time of the collision. Discovery revealed several alternative places for parking trailers for unloading and the 
failure of Weyerhauser to maintain reflectors on the side of the trailer, which resulted in a settlement of $120,000 in an otherwise impossible case. <i>Repetto v. 
Weyerhauser</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court Action No. 604529. </p>
<p><i>Collins v. Van Waters &amp; Rogers, </i>a products liability action, involved the first medically reported case of lip cancer secondary to repeated exposure to liquid 
chromate solvents used as cleaning agents in the manufacture of electronic components. Exposure occurred between 1979 and 1984. During this time the product 
carried warnings that it was hazardous and could cause death. While there had been no known cases of cancer caused by these compounds, a $250,000 recovery 
was obtained for the failure to warn of the cancer causing potential of these products. Settlement involved waiver of a $57,000 worker's compensation lien for 
previous benefits and an additional cash payment of $60,000 from the worker's compensation carrier. Total recovery $367,000 for a case of first impression. Santa 
Clara County Superior Court, 516914. </p>
<p>Confidential recoveries for five employees of Advanced Micro Devices fired with 700 others. In 1986, prior to discharge executives publicly announced they were 
ending the firm's longstanding no-layoff policy and planned to terminate &quot;laggards&quot;. Santa Clara County Superior Court Action Nos. 639523 &amp; 919143. </p>
<p>$1,732,500 recovered in two death cases resulting from the December, 1987 crash of PSA Flight 1771 when the flight crew was shot by a deranged suicidal killer. 
Killed in the crash was Deborah Neil, age 37, the senior cabin attendant and mother of Lauren, age 7. A graduate of San Jose's Blackford High School, Deborah 
joined PSA as a cabin attendant in 1970, married in 1978, and divorced in 1983. Lauren was Deborah's only child, who lived with her mother in Fremont, 
California. At her death Deborah had annual earnings of approximately $35,000. Also killed in the crash was Allen Swanson, age 45, who was survived by his only 
child, 17 year old daughter Jennifer, a high school senior, who lived with her mother following her parents divorce in 1985. Swanson, a former refining engineer, 
was Chevron's manager of public relations in Orange, Riverside, San Bernardino, and San Diego Counties, earning $72,000 per year. Each surviving child received 
$800,000, plus worker's compensation death benefits of $70,000, less $7,500 in repayment of worker's compensation liens. Los Angeles County Superior Court 
Action No. C671784. </p>
<p>$750,000 recovery for a head injury as a result of plaintiff rear ending a tractor and trailer which had turned into her lane of travel. <i>Lemley v. C&amp;C Warehouse 
Trucking</i>, San Joaquin County Superior Court Action No. 186124. </p>
<p>In <i>Barger v. Morrison Homes</i>, plaintiff, an employee of a framing contractor suffered a head injury when he fell from a second story of a single family home after 
the frame structure was struck by his employer's fork lift. In another Restatement 416 peculiar risk of harm case, the general contractor was sued for failing to take 
special precautions to prevent such an injury from occurring and settled prior to trial for $300,000 in cash, waiver of the worker's lien of $158,877.53 and a lifetime 
payment of $1,500 per month, which will pay plaintiff $1,953,731 over his lifetime. Contra Costa County Superior Court, 1987. </p>
<p><i>Yu v. A-1 Painting </i>resulted in a recovery of $150,000 for a 70 year old plaintiff, who was struck in a crosswalk. The primary challenge presented in this case was 
in proving medical care by Chinese physicians, with hospitalization and surgery in Taiwan. </p>
<p>In <i>Meyer v. Skillicorn</i> cattle escaped from a pasture and wandered onto Route 1 in Monterey County, near the Presidio. Meyer, a twenty year old from Missouri 
stationed at the Presidio of Monterey, was killed when his motorcycle collided with a cow. Settlement of $175,000 for both parents after setting aside a pre-case 
settlement of $75,000 negotiated by Missouri attorneys. <i>Meyer v. Skillicorn</i>, Monterey County Superior Court No. 82248. </p>
<p>In <i>Heffley v. Muller Berry Farms</i>, the plaintiff's 19 year old daughter and only child, lost her life in a rollover collision in which another teenager was killed and two 
others severely injured. A compromise settlement of $235,000 was negotiated on the eve of trial in Stanislaus County due to the insolvency of Cal Farm Insurance 
and resulting takeover by the California Insurance Guarantee Associates. Stanislaus County Superior Court Action No. 204208. </p>
<p>$400,000 wrongful death recovery for two sons who lost their 62 year old father and a son and daughter who lost their 64 year old mother, both residents of Texas 
vacationing in California when they were victims of a head-on collision. <i>Wigley v. Tru-Products,</i> Los Angeles County Superior Court Action No. NVC 5723. </p>
<p>$140,000 recovery for a mountain climber against the Sierra Club in <i>Shaoul v. Sierra Club</i>. Brought to the eve of trial fifteen months after the fall, the key issues in 
this case involved proving the plaintiff did not accept the risk of falling during a practice rock climbing session at Handley Rock, was not at fault in failing to check 
rigging used by others before him, and was not an uninvited recreational user for whom the Sierra Club was immune from suit. Because this was a case of 
extraordinarily difficult liability, this settlement represents an excellent recovery in what was clearly a defensible case. San Francisco Superior Court, No. 896640. 
September, 1989. </p>
<p>$178,500 recovery in Natchitoches Parish (Shreveport) Louisiana for a fractured humerus and closed head injury suffered by a University of California student 
when the vehicle in which she was a passenger collided with a tractor trailer parked on the roadway. The action was filed against the trucking company and her 
fiancee who was driving at the time of the collision. <i>Ryckebusch</i> v <i>JMS Trucking</i>, Natchitoches Parish No. 59,616(B). </p>
<p>Confidential settlement in <i>Doe v. Roe</i>, Santa Clara County Action numbers 605852 and 604450 on behalf of 8 children molested by a neighbor's teenage son. </p>
<p>In <i>Tonne v. Statewide Foreclosures</i>, three teenagers lost their mother when the Cessna 182 in which she was a passenger crashed into the ocean after departing 
Oceano County Airport. The aircraft was never recovered after the crash and the FAA reported the crash due to unknown reasons. In extensive recovery it was 
established that the pilot planned to make a left turn upon take-off and conduct a low level flight over friends vacationing on the beach. Plaintiffs contended the pilot 
had insufficient night flying experience to make an instrument turn on a dark moonless night that did not provide him with external visual references and that the pilot 
in flying his intended and announced route had flown the Cessna into the ocean. Witnesses on the ground claimed the aircraft caught on fire after they heard a loud 
bang and defendants claimed the crash, therefore was not due to pilot error. Settled at the beginning of trial for $600,000 on July 17, 1989. Santa Clara County 
No. 640888. Jury Verdict Reporter, volume 33, page 11, December 29, 1989.</p>
<p>In <i>Pedroza v. Westinghouse</i> an employee of Ray Wilson Construction Company fell 63 feet to his death from the top of a warehouse platform crane. Prior to his 
death Steven Pedroza, age 20, had climbed to the warehouse ceiling to plan for repairs to the roof and onto the horizontal beam of the crane which spanned the 
width of the building. Leaving the safety of the catwalk, he walked on the greased trolley track and fell. Despite overwhelming comparative negligence, a settlement 
of $435,000 was obtained for his family after investigation and discovery showed that Westinghouse security employees had provided his access to the crane 
building without providing an escort as required by Westinghouse company rules. In the absence of an escort, Pedroza did not comply with Westinghouse 
regulations which forbid anyone from climbing on a crane and which require all crane inspections to be conducted from safety scaffolds. Santa Clara County 
Superior Court No. 542030. </p>
<p>$87,500 recovery in <i>Byrnes v. Palo Alto Square, </i>Santa Clara County 597610. A 24 year-old computer systems programmer was injured when an elevator 
abruptly stopped between the fifth and sixth floors. Maintenance workers had left a ceiling hatch cover open on top of the elevator which collided with the elevator's 
counter-weights causing an emergency stop jarring plaintiff's back. Plaintiff suffered a herniated disc at L4-5, had previously had surgery at L4-5, and had a long 
history of low back pathology. Settled this difficult of medical causation against the building owners for new money and independent of the worker's compensation 
lien of $30,338. The worker's compensation carrier proceeded to trial and recovered nothing. The jury found Palo Alto Square was negligent BUT by a vote of 
12-0 held that its negligence was not a cause of plaintiff's injury. All of plaintiff's medical expenses of $21,281 were paid by the worker's compensation carrier and 
plaintiff was not required to repay $9,000 in temporary disability benefits previously received. Reported in California Jury Verdicts Weekly, September 1, 1989. </p>
<p><img src="car1.gif" alt="BMW Trunk Damage Close Up" align=right hspace=0 width=100 height=150> <img src="car2.gif" alt="BMW Crash Test" align=right hspace=0 width=270 height=150> $1,680,000 recovery for Dr. Paul Chin who was rear-ended in his 1969 BMW 1600 by a convicted felon who was intoxicated and traveling at 
90 miles per hour. The BMW exploded into a fireball and caused third degree burns to 65% of Dr. 
Chin's body. Following the collision, the BMW wreckage mysteriously disappeared near the time 
BMW's investigators photographed the scene and the bullet vehicle. An identical vehicle was lost in a 
nearly identical case arising in New York which was defensed by BMW in 1982. Crash testing of two 
full size BMW's proved the fuel system failed at low speeds in rear end collisions. This settlement was 
the first known occasion of a settlement by BMW in a case alleging a design defect. BMW models 
involved in this design include the 1600 and 2002 for 1966-73. Specially presented to the California 
Trial Lawyers' Association Winter Meeting, 1990. San Jose Mercury News, March 15, 1990; Palo 
Alto Times Tribune, March 15, 1990; Tacoma Morning News, March 16, 1990; The Arizona Republic, March 16, 1990; Fresno Bee, March 17, 1990; 
Automotive News, April 16, 1990; 9 Products Liability Law Reporter 144, October 1990. </p>
<p>$410,000 verdict for plaintiff in <i>Mills</i> v. <i>Community Development &amp; Management</i>, after rejecting a settlement offer of $27,800 for a cervical disc injury. Laura 
Mills was employed by California Commerce Bank when her heel pierced the carpeting and lodged in an uncovered hole in the concrete slab. During the six day 
trial plaintiff contended the carpeting company negligently inspected the premises and failed to permanently attach metal plates over holes with bolts or screws. 
Medical expenses $13,818, wage loss of $18,733, and future surgery costs of $15,000, plus six months loss of work to recuperate. Jury out four hours. $210,516 
in economic damages and $200,000 for pain and suffering apportioned 75% to carpet company and 25% to building manager. Plaintiff's employer found 60% at 
fault and workers' compensation lien of $28,077 rejected. San Jose Mercury, May 20, 1990. 33 ATLA Law Reporter 372. </p>
<p>In <i>Singh v. National Real Estate</i>, two year old Ciera Singh suffered brain damage when she and her father crossed a dark street and were stuck by an oncoming 
vehicle operated by a real estate salesman who was showing property to prospective customers on behalf of a local realty firm. Re-creation of the collision 
sequence with night photography and the testimony of accident reconstruction, bio-mechanical and human factors experts combined to show that the salesman's 
explanation of his speed and the collision sequence was unprovable. The broker was an independently owned and operated franchisee of a national real estate firm. 
The franchisor routinely avoided liability in similar cases throughout the United States, claiming that it was not responsible for its franchisee's torts, that it had no 
control over day-to-day operations and merely provided a trademark, logo, and national advertising program. By undertaking in-depth research of economic 
literature, retaining economists who have studied franchising, conducting a detailed investigation of operating policies, it was apparent that the creation of a national 
real estate network amounted to a joint venture. The confidential recovery was structured to provide a monthly stipend, increasing annually, to provide 
round-the-clock care for Ciera for the balance of her life. All funds are now administered through a bank's trust department, serving under court supervision. 
Because Ciera's care required prompt funding, this September 27, 1989 injury was brought to trial on July 30, 1990 and settled on July 31, 1990. In the interim, 
plaintiff's counsel offered 14 expert witnesses and completed discovery of an additional 29 parties, witnesses and defense experts, for a total of 43 pre-trial 
depositions. Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 693716. For legal analysis, see <i>Proving a National Real Estate Franchisor's Joint Venture Tort Liability</i>, 
20 CTLA Forum 221 (1990). </p>
<p>$100,000, policy limits, recovery in <i>Tejnil v. Yem</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 687474 arising from an automobile collision in which the injured-owner 
suffered a head injury and as a result did not recall any of the events involving, or preceding, the collision. The defendant driver, a high school classmate of the 
plaintiff, reported to police that he recalled driving his friend's sports car. Defendant located a witness who reported seeing the car speed pass him and<i> seeing the 
defendant in the passenger's seat.</i> At the crash site he again identified the plaintiff behind the wheel and the defendant in the passenger's seat, both unconscious. 
Defendant insurance carrier, facing an exposure well above its coverage, offered its $100,000 coverage the morning of trial. </p>
<p>Scott Cunningham, an aspiring pre-med student, suffered a traumatic hearing loss when a automobile battery exploded while he was &quot;jump&quot; starting a co-worker's 
car. The exploded battery was discarded the day of the explosion and in a short time the car was sold. After locating the car in Nevada, an inspection of the engine 
compartment confirmed the explosion path and a pattern of debris commonly left by an explosion of a defective battery. Repair records of the original owner 
revealed the manufacturer of the battery. The battery had been designed with two &quot;gang&quot; caps on the top of the battery that were each intended to plug three 
separate battery cells and to be held in place by compression. Accordingly any unit difference would result in leakage of hydrogen gas, which is acutely present in 
batteries that have been run down and in need of charging. Leaking hydrogen gas from automobile batteries readily explodes when ignited by a spark from jumper 
cables and for that reason the absence of individually screwed caps and warning labels was mandated. After an eight day jury trial in Santa Clara County Superior 
Court, the jury found for the defense and later explained that the absence of the actual defective battery was fatal to the plaintiff's case of design and product defect. 
<i>Cunningham v. Union 76 and GNB, Inc.</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court Action Number CV 698137, Honorable Robert Ahern, May, 1991. </p>
<p>$274,867 verdict, after rejecting a $20,000 settlement offer, by a 12-0 vote in <i>Adisa v. Yellow Cab</i>, San Francisco Superior Court No. 888921. Yellow Cab 
claimed that its driver had not &quot;blown&quot; a stop sign and that plaintiff had caused his own injuries as a result of speeding at 35-40 mph in a 25 mph residential area, 
was a convicted felon, and had received medical care for previous injuries to his neck. Defendants claimed at trial that plaintiff had suffered a neck strain which 
should have resolved in 6 to 8 weeks and that he could work as an operating engineer. Because of the lack of proof that plaintiff's bulging discs were in fact caused 
by this collision, the settlement demand was $300,000. Defendant offered $20,000 in settlement; the settlement conference judge valued the case at $125,000 to 
$150,000. Medical damages were $16,876. Following argument when defense counsel boasted that he expected a defense verdict, he was told the verdict would 
be $275,000. After a five day trial before Judge Pro Tem Craig Needham the jury deliberated for a day before rendering its verdict for $274,867, which was the 
largest single loss suffered by Yellow Cab in San Francisco in the previous ten years according to defense counsel. The verdict was 12-0 as to negligence, 
causation, and damages. Judgment entered March 11, 1991; paid March 13, 1991. Reported in California Jury Verdicts Weekly, August 16, 1991. </p>
<p>In February, 1991, an extremely broad gag order in <i>Vagshenian v. Palo Alto Unified School District,</i> Santa Clara County Action No. 687672, was imposed by 
the Court after jury selection, opening statements, and the testimony of Dr. Gregory Vagshenian. The San Jose Mercury News, July 29, 1989, reported that a nine 
year old boy was burned by a model rocket engine that shot up his sleeve. At the time the youngster, a third grader at Ohlone School, was attending a science fair 
at school and was observing a demonstration set up by Roland Horne, a Stanford professor. The experiment was intended to demonstrate how a rocket would 
burn in the absence of oxygen. According to one witness, the rocket was tied to one end of a pole with the other end of the pole placed in a bucket of water. When 
the rocket was ignited it flew off the pole and lodged itself near Erik's right armpit. Suit was filed against the Palo Alto Unified School District, the boy's teacher and 
the Stanford University engineering professor who set off the rocket, according to the Mercury. Under the gag order the victim and attorneys are only allowed to 
say: &quot;The matter is concluded.&quot; Sealed by Order May 2, 1991. </p>
<p><i>DeBruin v. Beach</i> arose from an assault by Dr. Christopher Beach, a chiropractor, upon Dr. Michael DeBruin, a chiropractor, who was dating Beach's estranged 
wife Dr. Cindy Gambelli, also a chiropractor. Beach's carriers denied coverage, but contributed a total of $50,000 towards a stipulated judgment of $150,000. 
Beach claimed that he was temporarily insane when he found Dr. DeBruin visiting his estranged wife; Dr. Beach was engaged during the pendency of his divorce, 
the divorce became final one month after the assault, and Beach knew that Dr. DeBruin and Dr. Gambelli had spent their summer vacation traveling together in 
Europe. During the pendency of this case the California Supreme Court decided J.C. Penny Casualty Insurance Co. v. M.K. in favor of the insurance industry 
holding that criminal conduct that on its face is harmful is precluded from coverage, even when there is underlying psychopathology that is severe. Santa Clara 
County Superior Court No. 689762. Judgment entered March, 1991. </p>
<p>$100,000 recovery for a backhoe operator who failed to wear eye protection and lost an eye while replacing a steel bucket tooth with a steel hammer, in violation 
of the manufacturer's safety warnings and written warnings on the hammer. Original attorney consulted by plaintiff declined to take the case because of the victim's 
fault in causing his own injury. Investigation showed that the original H &amp; L fabricated digging tooth had been designed to be attached to a steel shank by the use of 
a ball peen hammer. Hensley USA, a casting foundry, produced the tooth as a casting of extreme hardness, knowing that the primary mode of attachment in the 
field was by hammering. Judicial arbitration resulted in an award for the defendants, confirming the difficult liability presented in this case. Settled April, 1991. 
<i>Jensen v. Hensley USA and J. I. Case Company, Case Power and Equipment</i>, Santa Clara No. 693826. </p>
<p><i>Ingvardsen</i> v.<i> Lucky Stores</i>, Santa Clara County No. 705350, because of aggressive representation, was one of the first defective product L-tryptophan 
poisoning cases to be set for trial [October 28, 1991] in California. June Ingvardsen, a 56 year old, Los Altos mother of three boys and paralegal assistant of 18 
years, consumed one bottle of the contaminated L-tryptophan, an essential amino acid and food supplement, in September, 1989. She began experiencing 
symptoms and was diagnosed with EMS in November, 1989. EMS is a painful and progressive, multi-system disease which causes permanent scarring and fibrosis 
to nerve and muscle tissues, continuing inflammation, and provokes a permanent change in the body's immune system. In October, 1990, a complaint was filed 
against Lucky Stores, Inc.; Showa Denko was sued by Lucky Stores and joined as a cross-defendant. Showa Denko's plan to delay Ms. Ingvardsen's case by 
consolidating all California L- tryptophan cases in Los Angeles was successfully opposed and discovery was actively pursued to bring the case to trial. The case 
settled immediately prior to trial in a day long settlement conference before the Hon. David Leahy. Pursuant to the demand of Lucky Stores and Showa Denko 
K.K. the settlement sum is confidential and neither counsel or plaintiffs are allowed to comment on the adequacy of the recovery. </p>
<p>Another confidential recovery in <i>Wyatt </i>v. <i>Longs Drugs</i> for EMS injuries caused by L-tryptophan. Settled prior to March, 1992 trial. </p>
<p>Confidential recovery against Showa Denko for contaminated L-tryptophan in <i>Selbach v. Stanford University Hospital</i>, Santa Clara County Action No. 704321. 
Settled May, 1992 prior to June 15, 1992 trial date. </p>
<p>Additional confidential recoveries against Showa Denko for contaminated L-tryptophan in <i>Aguiar v. Showa Denko</i>, <i>Bransford v. Showa Denko</i> and <i>Zigalo v. 
Showa Denko, </i>San Francisco Superior Court. </p>
<p>Served as a consultant to San Francisco attorney and assisted in a confidential recovery in <i>Bailey v. Showa Denko</i>, case in which the victim suffered eosinophilia 
leukemia. The Mayo Clinic EMS team of physicians had concluded that Mr. Bailey's leukemia was unrelated to the L-tryptophan he had taken. Immediately prior 
to the final day for disclosure of expert witnesses, The Alexander Law Firm was consulted and arranged for experienced physicians to evaluate the plaintiff's claims. 
Settled upon being called to trial for a sum thirteen times greater than plaintiff's counsel was willing to accept prior to contacting us. Verification available from Bruce 
Krell, Esq. 415-861-4414. </p>
<p>$210,000 recovery for a head injury in <i>Fierro v. Firestone</i>, in which a 16 inch tire was installed on a 16.5 inch wheel and exploded due to a defect in the bead 
splice. The defendant claimed the tire had been abused in the course of being installed and that plaintiff's drinking of six beers was a major contributing factor. 
Normally in this type of explosion both the tire manufacturer and the wheel manufacturer [there are only two in the United States, Budd and Kelsey-Hayes] are 
joined as defendants. Unfortunately prior counsel never named the wheel manufacturer, although he had represented the client for three years. Upon entry we 
attempted to serve the wheel manufacturer as a fictitious defendant and were denied the right to join Kelsey-Hayes, which we appealed and lost. Fortunately the 
expert hired by previous counsel was forced to retire due to health and age, which allowed us to retain a formidable expert for trial. With alcohol and misuse 
defenses, this case under the best of circumstances would be difficult to win, but with an empty chair defense due to the absence of Kelsey-Hayes any settlement 
was considered a victory. Fresno County Superior Court 379634-9. For a detailed explanation of tire explosions see Product Liability: Preventing Deaths From 
Tire Explosions Caused By Known Design Defects, 22 CTLA Forum 17, Sept. 1992. </p>
<p>Forty year old Santa Clara Traffic Officer suffered a fractured elbow and wrist, with permanent nerve damages resulting in forced retirement, when his motorcycle 
was struck by a vehicle making a u-turn. Retained June, 1991 and obtained a recovery of $925,000 on April 28, 1992. Worker's compensation lien of $133,000 
was compromised for $100,000, despite no employer's negligence, in exchange for a compromise and release of the workers' compensation claim. Medical 
specials of $33,000 and projected partial wage loss of $350,000 argued despite the fact that the plaintiff had found full-time employment as an investigator in the 
electronics industry. <i>Robert Dorsey v. Oregon Plan</i>, Santa Clara County Action No. 712292. </p>
<p><i>Stanford </i>v. <i>U.S.A.A</i>, San Mateo County Action Number 321766 involved a claim against a homeowner's insurer for defects in the construction of the foundation 
for a hillside home built in 1973 which caused expansive soils to unstabilize the residence. Defects first discovered in 1987 and suit filed in 1988. Case closed on a 
confidential basis May, 1992. </p>
<p>$247,649 verdict in <i>D Astarte v. San Francisco Chronicle</i> after the plaintiff rejected a joint settlement offer of $150,000 made by the Chronicle and Bayshore 
Cab Company for injuries received while as a passenger in a cab that collided with a newspaper truck, including an operated cervical disk. Verdict against 
Bayshore Cab 12-0 which had coverage of only $100,000. This trial was a calculated risk that was not successful. Honorable Roy Wonder, <i>D Astarte v. San 
Francisco Chronicle</i>, City and County of San Francisco Superior Court, No. 938939, June, 1993. </p>
<p>Largest known recovery in the United States - $1,450,000 - in an adoption fraud case on behalf of a 16 year old and his parents. The boy had been the victim of 
years of abuse as an infant when he was placed for adoption at age four. The adopting parents were told there had been one instance of abuse, but the actual extent 
of the abuse and the youngster's complete psychiatric history were concealed from both the adopting parents and the child's pediatrician. Years later, a severe 
personality disorder erupted which required hospitalization from age 13 to 17. Referred by a family attorney who had the case pending for three years with no 
progress, trial preparation began in mid-1991. After securing psychiatric, social work, economic, and life placement expert testimony, completing 20 depositions, 
and defeating multiple motions to dismiss, the case was called for trial on July 6 and settled on July 7, 1992. Extremely difficult legal liability presented because 
under California law the county was immune from liability for negligent misrepresentation and could only be held liable for willful acts for which the insurance carriers 
would not be responsible. In addition, under Prop 51, the Anti-Deep Pocket Law, the county was not responsible for the harm caused by the minor's family prior to 
the adoption and a jury could have found his natural parents and relatives substantially at fault for his current psychiatric condition. County had also raised a statute 
of limitations defense that the adopting parents were on notice of the child's severe problems within one year of the adoption and clearly within three years after he 
was adopted. <i>Forter v. County of San Mateo</i>, Action No. 332087. San Jose Mercury News, July 8, 1992, B-1; July 9, 1992, B-1, July 12, A-1. Peninsula 
Times Tribune, July 9, 1992, B-1. See Professional Liability, Vol. 22, No. 12, October, 1992, page 1: &quot;Wrongful Adoption, A New and Significant Tort.&quot; </p>
<p>Confidential recovery for the death of a 16 year old who lost his life in a rollover of a CJ-7 Jeep in <i>Mock v. Chrysler Corporation</i>, Fresno County Superior Court 
Action Number 442560-9. One of three sons, Aaron Mock, was driving on a two lane, paved farm road with a keg of beer enroute to a high school party. He 
executed a right turn at a higher than safe speed, drifted into the oncoming lane, and in attempting to maneuver the Jeep back to the right side of the roadway, lost 
control. Jeep's classic instability, due to a narrow wheel base, short overall length, and high center of gravity, resulted in the rollover. The seat belted passenger 
suffered minor injuries. Aaron Mock was thrown from his seat and crushed by the rollbar. In addition to the seat belt defense, father's previous separate counsel's 
pursuit of a claim against Fresno County for a dangerous condition of a public roadway provided Chrysler with Prop 51 defense that the roadway was a major 
contributing cause of the death. The roadway was not a cause of this rollover. <i>Settled July 1992 on a confidential basis at the demand of Chrysler and agreed 
to by surviving parents. </i></p>
<p>$950,000 recovery in <i>Takeuchi </i>and <i>Kamiya</i> v. <i>Keegan</i>, Monterey County Superior Court Number 92486, arising from a head-on collision on August 4, 1991 on 
Route 156 near U.S. 101. Mari Kamiya, a 28 year old Japanese development engineer with IBM Japan in Tokyo was visiting the Bay Area and sharing a Sunday 
excursion with Dr. Tatsu Takeuchi, a family friend research physicist with the Stanford Linear Accelerator when the collision occurred. Ms. Kamiya, a passenger, 
incurred $87,000 in medical expenses immediately following the crash for severe fractures to her right clavicle, left ulna [forearm] and a fracture of L-1 with 
Harrington instrumentation and fusion of T-10 through L-2 lumbar vertebrae. With these extensive injuries the defense pressed a seat belt defense which was 
disproved by our expert accident reconstruction and testimony of a biomechanical engineer which established that in high speed collisions substantial injuries are 
often suffered even with seat belts in place. Total recovery for Ms. Kamiya was $900,000. She is expected to enjoy a full recovery. Dr. Takeuchi suffered a 
penetrating wound to the knee and has fully recovered. His medical bills totaled $8,500 and he approved a recovery of $50,000. Trial date of September 21, 
1992. Case settled on September 11, 1992 at the second extended settlement conference. Aggressive preparation and a prompt referral by original attorney on 
August 14, 1991 resulted in this early and very good result. </p>
<p>$1,350,000 recovery in a defective product case where a model airplane caused a leg fracture. Plaintiff, a 48 year old United Airlines pilot, on October 15, 1989 
was struck by a high speed model airplane being clocked for speed at a sanctioned competition of the Academy of Model Aeronautics at Whittier Narrows. The 
crash of the model airplane and the injuries to plaintiff were caused by faulty construction, faulty pre-flight inspection, and the failure to conduct such races in 
protected fenced arenas. In addition, the standard AMA pre-flight pull test is believed to have caused the failure of fuselage bolts which caused the plane to fly out 
of control at a speed of 184 m.p.h. Because he was a co-participant in the racing competition and had started the doomed aircraft, the Academy claimed the 
plaintiff assumed the risk of this injury, although this was the first known case of such an injury occurring. Assumption of risk is a complete defense in recreational 
activities under recent decisions of California courts. Because of a non-union of the tibia and fibula, eleven medical procedures were required at a cost of $220,000. 
Fortunately plaintiff returned to return to work as a pilot. <i>Armstead</i> v. <i>Academy of Model Aeronautics</i>, Alameda County Superior Court No. H-150430-1 settled 
before Hon. Daniel Weinstein, retired judge of the Superior Court, Judicial Arbitration and Mediation Service, on September 8, 1992. </p>
<p>The evidence was in the victim s body in the case of a $550,000 recovery for the family of Tim Skaggs who died of leukemia in 1991 at age 40, having been 
exposed to Woodlife during the years 1971-72 while employed by Simpson Lumber Company in Arcata, California. In an investigation of three other leukemias at 
the Simpson mill by the State Department of Health, Simpson concealed from officials that for years it had used wood preservatives with pentachlorophenol. The 
state concluded this cancer cluster arose from unknown causes. The Alexander Law Firm undertook an extraordinarily detailed investigation which began with an 
indepth analysis of pentachlorophenol and other lawsuits in the United States. See <i>A Developing Toxic Tort: Lumber Mills, Log Cabins, Leukemia, 
Lymphomas and Soft Tissue Sarcomas - The Case Against Pentachlorophenol</i>, 21 CTLA Forum 195 (1991). Following numerous interviews of mill workers, 
many of whom had no recollection of Tim s part-time work on the paint line where Woodlife was applied twenty years ago, the paint line operator confirmed that 
Woodlife had been used in painting machines, but he had no recollection of Tim working there. Although Simpson s mill records no longer existed, its purchasing 
agent confirmed it had purchased Woodlife by the barrel from Champion International. Champion s sales manager of twenty years ago was located and he testified 
Woodlife was sold to the Arcata plant for use on the paint line. To prove Tim s exposure, a fat sample was taken from his abdomen and analyzed for dioxins and 
furans suspected to have contaminated Woodlife. After an extensive search, a twenty year old bucket of pentachlorophenol was located and tested, revealing an 
80% correlation between the pattern of dioxins found in Tim s fat and those found in the sample product. Settled April 29, 1993 before Judge Michael Brown, 
following the denial of Champion s motion for summary judgment and after the completion of expert depositions before the May 17th scheduled trial. <i>Skaggs v. 
Champion International</i>, Humboldt County Superior Court No. DR 85488. See also The Times Standard, May 6, 1993, page one. Served as lead counsel in 
three additional pentachlorophenol caused wrongful death recoveries. All are confidential. <i>Gordon v. U. S. Plywood- Champion Papers</i>, Humboldt County 
Superior Court Action No. 92 DR 0135; <i>Carper v. U. S. Plywood-Champion Papers</i>, Humboldt County Superior Court No. 92 DR 0378; <i>Freeman v. U.S. 
Plywood-Champion Papers</i>, Humboldt County Superior Court No. 93 DR 0275. </p>
<p><em>GM Pickup Gas Tank.</em> On July 3, 1996 a $5 billion dollar settlement of this national class action was announced. The <a href="http://www.seamless.com/alexanderlaw/txt/reserved.html">complete details</a> of the settlement can be 
found on this web site. The new settlement meets all the objections raised to a previous class action settlement for GM truck owners which was reversed by the 
Third Circuit Court of Appeals and by the Texas Court of Appeals. All lawsuits against GM filed in federal courts across the United States were transferred to the 
U. S. District Court in Philadelphia under federal Multi-District Litigation rules. The Alexander Law Firm represents 278 of 283 
plaintiffs before the Honorable William H. Yohn, Jr. Our case was the only one entitled to be heard under federal court jurisdiction rules because it is based on the 
U. S. Magnusson-Moss Act for breach of warranty, which requires 100 plaintiffs to prosecute a class action. Our contribution to the legal team focused on our 
practical experience in gas tank failure cases: retention of experts and preparation of direct testimony of liability experts for preliminary motions and trial focusing on 
defects in the saddlebag tank, proposed alternative placement and designs which would maintain fuel system integrity. <em>In re: General Motors Corporation Pickup 
Truck Fuel Tank Products Liability Litigation</em>, U.S. District Court, Eastern District of Pennsylvania, MDL No. 961, Master File No. 92-6450. San Jose 
Mercury News, August 27, 1993; Wall Street Journal, December 17, 1993. The federal court plaintiffs by agreement with attorneys in state cases filed across the 
South joined all cases for settlement purposes in the Louisiana state court where preliminary approval of a new settlement was given on July 3,1996. A final 
approval hearing will take place on November 6, 1996 and approval is expected. In the absence of an appeal the settlement will become effective in early January 
1997. New York Times, July 4, 1996, San Jose Mercury New July 4, 1996, San Francisco Chronicle July 4, 1996, Wall Street Journal July 5, 1996, Associated 
Press Wire Services July 3, 1996.</p>
<p>$48,000,000 national recovery in the Sears Automotive Repair Fraud action on behalf of consumers defrauded by Sears commission sales program for auto 
repairs. Filed in U.S. District Court in San Francisco and successfully concluded August, 1992. Participated as support counsel on the Plaintiffs Steering 
Committee. <i>In re Sears Automotive Center Consumer Litigation</i>, Action No. C-92-2227, Honorable Robert H. Schnacke. </p>
<p><a name="train"><img src="train2.gif" alt="photo" align=left hspace=0 width=300 height=200 heigth="200"></a>Spearheaded $15,500,000 recovery for the victims of the pollution of the Sacramento River of July, 1991 when 
a 19,000 gallon tank car derailed at the Cantara Loop spilling metam sodium and releasing methyl isothiocyanate, 
a respiratory irritant, affecting 3000 residents of the Dunsmuir and Lake Shasta area. Major responsibilities, as a 
member of the ten law firm steering committee for this class action, involved proof of medical causation, selection 
of experts in epidemiology, air dispersion, toxicology, occupational medicine, pulmonary medicine and psychiatry, 
and trial preparation. Active member of four attorney team that negotiated the final settlement. See San Francisco 
Chronicle, July 29, 1993. San Francisco Superior Court, <i>Sacramento River Spill Litigation</i>, Judicial Council 
Coordination Nos. 2617 and 2620. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
In <i>Plotkin v. General Electric,</i>The Alexander Law Firm led the nation in charging General Electric with defrauding the American public in the sale of Energy 
Choice Light Bulbs which were claimed to be energy efficient, required less electricity and would preserve the environment. In actuality, the 100 watt replacement 
bulb was simply a dimmer 90 watt bulb and was sold for twice the price of a standard 100 watt bulb. Embarrassed by the public exposure of misconduct, General 
Electric readily settled this national class action. Forty-four million Energy Choice Light Bulbs sold over a two year period. Settlement provides for national 
reimbursement by special coupons to all consumers refunding overcharges. <i>Plotkin v. General Electric</i>, U.S. District Court, Northern District of California, Action 
No. C-92-4447, Honorable Barbara Caufield. See San Francisco Chronicle, October 28, 1993, page 2. </p>
<p>$200,000,000 estimated total recovery for 33,000 owners of 1987-90 Nissan minivans which were the subject of three recalls because of engine failures and fires 
before The Alexander Law Firm filed suit in April 1993. On February 2, 1994, one week before the hearing on plaintiff s motion to certify a national class action, 
Nissan negotiated a settlement of the class action, stipulated to the certification of a national class, and resolved a federal investigation by the National Highway 
Traffic and Safety Administration by voluntarily agreeing to an unprecedented buy back of 33,000 vans at fair market value [$5,000 to $7,000]. <i>Johnson v. Nissan 
Motor Company In U.S.A.</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 730558. Wall Street Journal, February 4, 1994, page A2. San Jose Mercury, C1, San 
Francisco Chronicle, A5. </p>
<p>$850,000 recovery for Cherie and Mark Collister as a result of being defrauded by Tulare County social workers when they adopted Katrina. The birth mother s 
history of schizophrenia, mental retardation, and institutional confinement was never revealed to the adopting parents, but aggressive trial preparation confirmed the 
county at all times knew the birth mother s history and the county s employees never advised the adopting parents of Katrina s debilitating disabilities. Because 
Katrina s schizophrenia was congenital and inevitable, Katrina was not harmed by the county s fraud. Mark and Cherie for opening their home and their hearts to 
this youngster were forced to suffer 10 years of living with a tragically mentally ill child. The parents recovery against the county represents the parents general 
damages for personal pain and suffering. <i>Collister v. County of Tulare</i>, Tulare County Superior Court Action No. 93-159371. Filed August, 1993; settled 
September 6, 1994. See Fresno County Bee, September 7, 1994. </p>
<p>On Christmas Day, 1991 four teenage boys, Jason St. John, Christopher Benjamin, Jesse Cepeda and Edwin Martin, were burned to death when a 1978 four 
wheel drive Dodge Ramcharger over-turned at 20 miles per hour and landed on its roof in a creek bed. The case settled in April, 1994 after two years of extensive 
trial preparation which showed that Chrysler anticipated this vehicle would roll in the field and for that reason installed a rollbar in the passenger compartment, while 
allowing the rear mounted filler tube, which was bolted to sheet metal at the rear of the vehicle to remain unprotected in a rollover. None of the boys suffered any 
orthopedic injuries and this single vehicle crash would have been readily survivable if the fuel system had not failed. Chrysler knew that this covered pickup truck 
design lacked rear end structural stability, but nonetheless the company hard mounted the gas tank filler tube to the side of the vehicle that was sure to fail in a 
rollover. Other vehicles sold by Chrysler in 1978 had breakaway filler tubes to avoid the type of failure well documented in both full-size Fords [see Claudine 
Brown and Caryl Meslo v. Ford Motor Company above] and Pintos. We represented all four families. One of the most emotionally challenging cases we have 
encountered in twenty-five years of practice. This case is every parent s nightmare. These boys were doing nothing terribly wrong, had not been drinking and should 
have survived if the fuel system had performed properly. They were outstanding youngsters, good students, respected athletes, and full of live. For their families 
Christmas Day will never again be the same. The total recoveries at the request of both Chrysler Corporation and the families is not to be revealed. The amounts 
that were paid were those that I recommended. It was, and will always be, an honor to represent these families. <i>Howard and Mary St. John, Fran and Wendy 
Benjamin, Phill and Gayle Martin and Arthur and Deborah Cepeda v. Chrysler Corporation</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 722446. Filed April, 
1992; settled April, 1994 following the completion of all expert discovery by the Hon. Daniel Weinstein, JAMS, San Francisco. For details see December 26, 
1991 San Jose Mercury News, page one. </p>
<p>In <i>Evarkiou v. Ford Motor Company, </i>U.S. District Court, Northern District of California, No. C-93-0844-SAW, an action on behalf of a proposed nationwide 
class of 429,000 owners of 1988-91 3.8 Liter Ford Taurus, Mercury Sable and Lincoln Continental, we sought relief as a result of power steering hoses that were 
prone to rupture due to a design defect resulting in loss of steering and possibly fires. This action sought recovery for property damage and injunctive relief. 
Discovery established that engine fires were caused by improper service work that resulted in dislocation of the power steering hoses and improper repositioning by 
mechanics. In a unique settlement, in which no class member released any claim, Ford agreed to issue a Technical Service Bulletin addressing this problem and to 
sell power steering hoses only in special boxes containing the TSB, all appropriate warnings and installation instructions with the appropriate heat shield and tie 
straps at a 30% discount. In addition the TSB was issued to all dealers and associations of mechanics. Total value of the benefit conferred is approximately 
$2,000,000. </p>
<p>The winter of 1993 left the Bay Area in sub-freezing temperatures but Caltrans did not give a second's thought to the fact that mountain springs that cross the Route 
17 south of San Jose would cover the roadway with ice well before the valley floor froze. Prior to January 3, 1993, a series of seven collisions occurred at the same 
location due to ice on the roadway. On the evening of January 3, Judith Manning was northbound on Route 17 when she lost control of her Jeep Cherokee as it slid 
across black, invisible ice and crossed the roadway where she invaded the path of Christopher Smith who was headed southbound. Smith died in the collision 
leaving a wife and three young children. We represented Ms. Manning who suffered a ruptured bladder, punctured lung and fractures of the pelvis and ribs. She 
obtained a recovery of $300,000 against the State. The Smith family recovered $725,000 against the State and $25,000 from Ms. Manning, leaving Ms. Manning 
with a net recovery of $275,000. Closed September 22, 1994. <i>Manning v. State of California</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court No. 731042. </p>
<p>In <i>Varvais v. State of California</i>, Kathleen Matheson was driving southbound of Highway 49 through a construction zone under contract with Granite 
Construction Company and supervised by Caltrans. Ms. Matheson s vehicle dropped four inches off the surfaced roadway onto the right shoulder. As she 
attempted to regain the road, she over corrected and turned directly into the path of the Varvais family. Both vehicles were travelling at 35-40 mph and all 
occupants were seat belted. In the collision of August 13, 1992, Kathleen Matheson and her two month old son Brennan were killed. We represented the Varvais 
family. Kristen Varvais, age 8, was killed. Cindy Varvais, mother and driver, suffered torn ankle ligaments, rib fractures, collapsed right lung and a sprained knee. 
Jordan Varvais, age 9, sustained a closed head injury, and fractures of the skull, T-6 [compression] and ankle. Lindsay Varvais, age 6, suffered limited physical 
injuries and emotional distress. Placer County is a rural county in the Sierra Mountain where the primary industries are lumber, cattle and summer recreation 
activities. The county has a history of pro-defendant verdicts, no recorded verdicts against the State Department of Transportation, and the handful of plaintiffs 
verdicts have been extremely low. A focus group showed conclusively that local residents appreciate and think highly of Caltrans, no matter what errors in 
supervision or judgment were made, and that local jurors were hostile to out- of-county visitors such as Ms. Matheson. The total recovery for the Varvais family 
was only $350,000 for total losses which would have been recognized as having a value of $1,000,000 or more in any major jurisdiction. Unfortunately cases 
against the State of California for defective roadways must be brought in the county where the loss occurred. Another law firm representing the Matheson losses 
was made a zero offer by the State and suffered a defense verdict in July, 1994, confirming our pre-trial analysis. <i>Varvais v. State of California</i>, Placer County 
No. SCV 01222. </p>
<p>A court-approved settlement of a consumer class action settlement against Bausch &amp; Lomb was announced on August 1, 1996. Under the settlement Bausch &amp; 
Lomb will pay up to $68 million in cash and products to 1.5 million buyers of the company's disposable lenses. Many wearers will receive from $25 to $50 in cash 
and $25 to $50 in coupons under the settlement as a result of a class-action filed in May 1994 which alleged that the company sold the same product under 
different brand names at widely varying prices and engaged in a fraudulent marketing scheme in order to gain market share in the disposal lens market. The result 
was that some consumers paid much more because they believed they were getting different lenses. <em>Roberts v. Bausch &amp; Lomb, Inc.</em>,U.S. District Court, Northern 
District of Alabama, Western Division, No. CV-94-C-1144-W. See Wall Street Journal, November 2, 1994 and August 2, 1996 [B-2].</p>
<p>$500,000 recovery for the family of Edward Peterman, age 73, who lost his life on a rural road in San Benito County on February 24, 1994 when an employee of a 
car dealer fell asleep at the wheel and struck Mr. Peterman s pick-up head on. A retired Air Force colonel, he flew 65 missions over German occupied territory in 
WWII and was the recipient of the Distinguished Flying Cross with Oak Leaf Cluster and the Air Medal with nine clusters. Mr. Peterman was active as an 
insurance agent in the Gilroy area, maintained regular office hours and at the time of his death was delivering policies to customers. He was survived by his wife of 
27 years and two adult children: a college professor and a deputy county sheriff. Our clients elected to settle their claims for the available insurance policy limits in 
July, 1994 immediately prior to filing suit. We were proud to be selected to represent this family and to help them conclude their case in a dignified and prompt 
manner. </p>
<p>Confidential recovery in <i>Blair v. Agency Rent-A-Car, Inc.</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court, Consolidated Action Nos. 735492 and 736954. Kristin Blair, age 
21, daughter of Patricia and Randolph Blair, accepted a ride home from a Grateful Dead concert on August 23, 1993 in an Agency Rent-A-Car van that was 
driven by an unlicensed teenage driver. Agency Rent-A-Car held responsible for negligent entrustment of a vehicle. February, 1995.</p>
<p><i>Guerrant v. Forbricht</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court action number 729175, involved sexual harassment and molestation by a prostheticist, who would 
touch his stepdaughters at night while they slept and who installed a false heating vent for peeping into the youngsters' bathroom. Confidential recovery. April, 1995.</p>
<p>A $1,000,000 recovery for Nicole Freeburn represents only partial compensation for traumatic brain injury to a 16 year old who was thrown from a utility vehicle 
that carried five teenagers, but seatbelts for only four passengers. The owner and driver carried primary policy limits of $100,000/$300,000 and a $1,000,000 
excess policy was shared with another injured passenger. This case illustrates the need for everyone,especially parents of teenagers, to purchase and keep in force 
excess Uninsured/Underinsured coverage on their own vehicles. A family excess liability and underinsured insurance rider providing coverage in excess of 
$1,000,000 would have been extremely valuable in this case. <i>Freeburn v. Wehman</i>, Santa Clara County Superior Court action number 742048; consolidated with 
746364. Filed July 1994; settled May, 1995.</p>
<p>$750,000 recovery for the family of Joseph Pickering, a 38 year old high school teacher, who died in 1994. Mr. Pickering during the early 1970s was employed by 
Chevron at its pesticide bottling plant in California and was exposed to Weed-B-Gone. The main ingredients of this pesticide during the early 1970s were 2,4 D 
and 2,4,5 TP. A search of local homes produced twenty year old cans of Weed-B-Gone that when tested proved to be contaminated with dioxins and furans. Mr. 
Pickering died of a soft-tissue sarcoma which has been identified in medical literature as being associated with the contaminants found in this common household 
pesticide. This case again proved that chemical exposure cases are the most challenging and most expensive of the defective product cases. Mr. Pickering was 
survived by his wife and three children. All discovery was completed when this case settled in June, 1995 at the third pre-trial settlement conference conducted by 
Judge Daniel Weinstein, JAMS, San Francisco. <i>Pickering v. Chevron Chemical Company and Dow Chemical Company</i>, San Francisco Superior Court 
Action Nos. 938467 and 952025. (Posted June 27, 1995).</p>
<p>Chrysler Minivans. We are one of eight firms in the United States that filed suit seeking correction of defective rear hatch door lock failures in nominal impacts for 
3,300,000 owners of Chrysler minivans. Actions were filed in Santa Clara County Superior Court, U. S. District Court for the Northern District of California, and 
state courts in New York, Louisiana, Texas and Alabama. Because door locks are not subject to any federal motor vehicle safety standard, the National Highway 
Traffic Safety Administration had limited authority to force a recall absent Chrysler's willingness to do so. Chrysler announced a &quot;service action&quot; and its intention to 
replace all such locks on March 27, 1995 the day before our motion for class certification was set to be heard in Santa Clara County Superior Court. These related 
class actions resulted in a negotiated settlement under which Chrysler became contractually bound to all owners of 1984 through 1995 Chrysler minivans to replace 
existing rear hatch door locks. Chrysler estimates that the total cost of this contractual recall is approximately $120,000,000. <em>Mann v. Chrysler Corporation</em> 
Santa Clara County Superior Court Action number CV 746017. The provisional settlement agreement of July 21, 1995 was given final approval by Judge Charles 
A. Legge on November 30, 1995, <em>Stuart Hanlon, et al v. Chrysler Corporation</em>, U.S. District Court, Northern District of California, Civil Action No. C 
95-2010 CAL. Despite several objections, Judge Legge held that the settlement was &quot;fair, reasonable and adequate.&quot; See The Recorder, December 1, 1995, page 
1; San Francisco Daily Journal, December 1, 1995, page 1. </p>
<p><a name="chemical"><img src="richchem.gif" alt="Richmond Chemical Plant Aerial View" align=right border=1 hspace=0 width=200 height=263></a> $180,000,000 Final Settlement. The Richmond Toxic Cloud class action litigation, Contra Costa County Superior Court, arose 
from the explosion of a tank car of oleum, concentrated sulfuric acid and sulfuric trioxide, in July, 1993 at the sulfuric acid 
manufacturing plant operated by General Chemical Company in Richmond, California. General Chemical was the sole provider of 
sulfuric acid to Chevron's Northern California gasoline refinery. In the aftermath of the explosion, which sent 12 tons of oleum into 
the atmosphere, 63,000 Californians were exposed and thousands were seen at hospital emergency rooms for chemical exposure. 
As one of seven firms appointed by the Court to manage this massive toxic chemical class action, our mission was to prove 
medical causation and the full range of injuries caused by this disaster and to serve as Chair, Science/Medical Causation 
Committee. As an active member of the Class Action Executive Committee and the Plaintiffs' Management Committee, which was 
responsible for overseeing and prosecuting this combined class and mass tort action, our responsibilities included formulating, 
planning and executing the organization of the plaintiffs' proof of scientific and medical evidence including the retention of a 
mutli-disciplinary team of meterologists, atmospheric scientists, and computer modeling scientists to conduct a detailed study of the 
sulfuric acid plume caused by the venting of acid into the atmosphere, participation in the execution of the computerized windfield 
and plume study to identify and replicate the path and concentrations of the cloud of sulfuric acid as it dispersed, selection and 
screening of class representatives for the Model Complaint, retention of experts in toxicology, occupational medicine, 
pulmonology and allergy medicine, participation in focus group presentations, preparing and appearing with our 14 class representatives at their depositions and 
active involvement in extended settlement discussions leading to the final recovery of $180,000,000. </p>
<p>In addition we conducted an aerial reconnaissance and inspection of General Chemical's sister facility in Wilmington, Delaware which revealed barns and sheds for 
housing tank cars, unlike the Richmond facililty where loading and unloading of tank cars occurred in the open. The settlement,which was negotiated during the 
winter and spring of 1995 was first announced on June 20, 1995 and reported by the San Francisco Chronicle, San Jose Mercury, Associated Press and PR Wire 
on June 21, 1995. The final approval hearing was held on October 27, 1995. The Court rendered its final decision confirming the settlement on November 13, 
1995. This outstanding result occurred as a result of a team effort that successfully proved outrageous misconduct in the heating of the tank car which exploded, 
carefully selected class representatives, diligently marshalled medical and scientific evidence and created a computerized program for reporting exposures and 
injuries for each of the 63,000 claimants. For more information see <em>In re GCC Richmond Works Case</em>, Judicial Council Coordination Proceeding No. 2906, 
Contra Costa County Superior Court, Martinez, California. </p>
<p>On June 8, 1994 a 65 pound smoke bomb exploded on the campus of Palo Alto's Gunn High School causing serious injuries to two high school women and 
requiring medical treatment for 16 others. Because of decisions by the California Supreme Court which have denied insurance coverage for intentional conduct 
which accidentally results in unintended injury, collecting damages for the injured in this case was a challenge. We were happy to obtain recoveries of $100,000 and 
$50,000 for our clients. For a detailed report of this case see The Consumer Law Page &quot;Explosive Devices, Public Schools, and Lenient School Administrators: 
The June 8, 1994 Smoke Bomb Prank at Gunn High&quot; at <a href="http://www.seamless.com/alexanderlaw/txt/explode.html">http://www.seamless.com/alexanderlaw/txt/article/explode.shtml</a>. <em>Catherine Meyer and Eleanor Lin v. 
Palo Alto Unified School District</em>, Santa Clara County Superior Court Civil Action No. 746309 and <em>Catherine Meyer and Eleanor Lin v Robert Roberts, 
Brendan Wheatley, David Chin</em>, Santa Clara County Superior Court Civil Action No. 742428, <em>Fire Insurance Exchange [Farmers Insurance Company] v. 
Brendan Wheatley, Catherine Meyer and Eleanor Lin, Robbie Roberts, David Chin</em>, Santa Clara County Superior Court Civil Action No. 745540. For further 
information see Time Magazine May 8, 1995 [photo, page 56]; San Jose Mercury News, June 10, June 11, June 18, June 23, July 1, July 7, August 15, 
November 18, 1994; January 7, February 4, 1995; January 3, 1996; San Francisco Chronicle, June 18, July 7, July 23, 1994; Palo Alto Weekly, June 22, 
December 2, 1994; February 8, February 28, 1995; January 5, 1996. </p>
<p>On March 29, 1993 Larry Kohler and Joe Orlando, business lines agents of Nationwide Insurance filed an action against Nationwide in the Superior Court of the 
State of California for the County of San Francisco which was removed to the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California, <em>Lawrence B. Kohler and 
Joseph Orlando v. Nationwide Mutual Insurance Company, Employers Insurance of Wausau, et al</em>, Civil Action No. C 93-1584 SC alleging that Nationwide 
engaged in various acts including breached their contract for failure to pay delayed compensation, for improper chargebacks to extended earnings payments, by 
making changes in the Nationwide contract, breached their implied-in-fact contract for good cause termination, breached an implied-in-fact contract for exclusivity 
and alleging that Wausau tortiously interfered with contract. After completing all discovery, prior to the January, 1996 trial date, a settlement conference before the 
Honorable Eugene Lynch resulted in an amicable settlement which is confidential. In January, 1996, Nationwide Insurance and Employers Insurance of Wausau 
retained The Alexander Law Firm to furnish advisory and consulting services for a period of five years. Under the retainer agreement the firm is not 
prohibited from representing any party in an action against an insured of Nationwide or Wausau in which the issues or facts litigated in Kohler and Orlando are not 
in issue. Nationwide, the fifth largest casualty insurer in the United States with total assets of $35 billion, has issued public reports confirming its retention of 
The Alexander Law Firm. </p>
<p>Allstate Insurance Agents. With our co-counsel we represented 1,809 California Allstate Insurance agents who had not been reimbursed for the cost of maintaining 
Allstate offices under R830, R1500 or R3000 employment contracts between January 1, 1990 and April 30, 1996. Although these agents legally were employees 
of Allstate, Allstate required them to personally pay for the costs of operating company offices under its Neighborhood Office Agency program. Under the 
California Labor Code, employees cannot be forced to pay for an employers' business expenses as a condition of employment. In January, 1995 the court certified 
this case as a class action and final settlement was approved on March 20,1996. With the settlement of this case Allstate simultaneously decided to convert all 
employee agents to independent contractors in order to operate its agent network in conformance with California law. Of the total of 2,288 agents, 304, 
representing 13% of the agent force, have chosen to opt-out of the settlement and to pursue individual claims against Allstate. Under class action procedures, the 
filing of a class action tolls every class ' statute of limitations and the opt-out agents are now able to go forward at this late date to attempt through their individual 
attorneys to litigate with Allstate over reimbursement terms and to contest Allstate's changing their status from employees to independent contractors. Although on 
this latter issue, in response to the objection of several agents, the National Labor Relations Board has concluded that Allstate's decision was made for lawful 
business reasons. By mid-June, 1996 1,334 of 1,809 claimants had received reimbursements of $6,170,000. In addition to receiving reimbursement of office 
operating expenses, one of the benefits of the settlement is the recognition of the agent's ownership interest in his book of business one year from the date of 
conversion to independent contractor status. Without the settlement an agent would have had to wait five years from conversion under Allstate's previous rules in 
order to be able to sell his or her book of business acquired prior to conversion. Many agents are expected to sell their book of business to other agents in the 
Spring of 1997. This case is the second case for insurance agents that we concluded in 1996 [see<em> Kohler and Orlando v. Nationwide</em>]. In re Insurance Agent 
Cases I and II, J. C. C.P.Nos. 2984 and 2985, Alameda County Superior Court before Hon. Joseph Carson.</p>
<p><font size=2>Updated August 1996</font></p>
