<h2>Survivors of Sexual Assault: </h2>
<h3>A General Information Guide for Women, Their Families and Counselors </h3>
<h3>By Richard Alexander, Editor </h3>
<hr>
<p><strong>Published in 1978 </strong></p>
<p><strong>Important Special Announcement</strong></p>
<p>This book was first published in 1978 as special project of the Santa Clara County Bar Association and the Santa Clara 
County Criminal Justice Advisory Board. At the time I served as the chair of the county justice advisory board and was a 
Trustee of the Santa Clara County Bar Association. A committee was formed to produce a brochure for women who had 
been assaulted, but like many such efforts the tasks fell on the committee chair and over a period of six months I compiled the 
information that became this book. I claim no authorship, but merely borrowed, re-wrote and brought together the work of 
those acknowledged below into one document so it could be a ready reference, adding my own perspective and experience 
throughout. As part of a special project at San Jose State University, 15,000 copies of the book were printed and circulated. 
It was well used for many years as a training manual for rape counselors. </p>
<p>The information contained here has not been updated. I leave that task to others. This book should only be used as a general 
guide and it obviously is not legal advice, that can only come from a lawyer in your state who knows the law and the facts of 
your case. </p>
<p>This book now is offered on the internet as a general guide for anyone to use to develop a resource manual for survivors of 
sexual assault in their community, rather than simply gather dust on my library shelf. I hope someone can and will use this 
material to benefit others. That was my original intention when I compiled this information. This book may be copied and used 
by any non-profit organization with my permission, and best wishes, just please send an email to access@alexanderlaw.com 
notifying me that the material is being put to good use or write me at P. O. Box 1330, San Jose, CA 95109-1330. </p>
<p>Originally this book was titled &quot;Rape Crisis: The Victim's Right.&quot; I have changed the title in this re-publishing to focus not on 
&quot;victimization,&quot; which as a concept empowers criminals, rapists and abusers, and instead have chosen to place the emphasis 
where it properly belongs: on surviving, overcoming and living. To those who struggle to do that and to those who love and 
care for them, I respectfully dedicate this re-publication. </p>
<p>Richard Alexander<br>
The Consumer Law Page [http://consumerlawpage.com]<br>
San Jose, California<br>
October, 1996. </p>
<p><strong>Acknowledgments</strong></p>
<p>Special thanks for their assistance in completing this publication are due to: </p>
<ul>
<li>California Department of Justice </li>
<li>California State University Police, San Jose </li>
<li>California Young Lawyers Association </li>
<li>Los Angeles County Commission on the Status of Women </li>
<li>Mental Health Association of Santa Clara County </li>
<li>Mexican American Community Services Agency (MACSA) </li>
<li>Mid-Peninsula Rape Crisis Center/YWCA </li>
<li>Queen's Bench Foundation, San Francisco </li>
<li>Rape Prevention Education Committee, San Jose State University </li>
<li>Rape Prevention Education Committee, University of California, </li>
<li>Berkeley San Jose Police Department Santa Clara County Bar </li>
<li>Association Santa Clara County Commission on the Status of </li>
<li>Women Santa Clara County Criminal Justice Advisory Board Santa </li>
<li>Clara County District Attorney's Office Santa Clara County </li>
<li>Mental Health Department Santa Clara County Office of Education </li>
<li>Santa Clara Valley Medical Center Women's Collective, Stanford </li>
<li>YWCA/Valley Rape Crisis Center </li>
</ul>
<p>Recognition is due to Theresa Canepa, Assistant Editor; to Jackye Read, Program Director, YWCA/Valley Rape Crisis 
Center; to Susan St. John, Program Director, Mid-Peninsula Rape Crisis Center; to Charles B. DeWitt, Director, Justice 
Division, office of the County Executive of Santa Clara County; to Thomas Hanford and Robert L. Webb, Santa Clara 
County District Attorney's Office; to Jette Garland, Office of the Public Defender, Santa Clara County, and to Adele Bihn, 
Coordinating Council on Services to Survivors of Sexual Assault, who offered valuable advice and suggestions for the project. </p>
<p>The strong support and encouragement of Santa Clara County Supervisors Susanne Wilson, Dominic L. Cortese, Dan 
McCorquodale, Rod Diridon and Geraldine Steinbert is gratefully appreciated. </p>
<p><strong>Introduction</strong></p>
<p>Rape is a crime of violence carried out through sexual means. One out of ten women can expect to be assaulted during her 
lifetime. Any woman can be raped - regardless of race, age or occupation - anywhere, anytime. Although men are sexually 
assaulted too, by other men, the primary targets are women. </p>
<p>The Santa Clara County Bar Association prepared this booklet as a public service to women in Santa Clara County. The 
booklet's focus is not on rape prevention, but on the Survivor's personal experience, and on her involvement with agencies 
such as police, hospitals, district attorneys' offices, courts and mental health facilities. </p>
<p>Why is this important? </p>
<p>Because rape is traumatic and knowledge of the Survivor's needs, her rights, where to go for help and what she can expect to 
feel will help her survive the trauma. </p>
<p>The chapters of the book represent the steps in the legal/medical process which follow a rape. </p>
<p>Chapter I describes the law, some of the myths surrounding rape, and precautionary measures. </p>
<p>Chapter II describes the emotional aftermath of rape for both women and men, and discusses mental health services. </p>
<p>Chapter III describes police procedures. </p>
<p>Chapter IV discusses emergency room procedures and medical after care. </p>
<p>Chapter V describes the district attorney's role and municipal court procedures. </p>
<p>Chapter VI describes superior court procedures. </p>
<p>Chapter VII discusses compensation for the rape Survivor. </p>
<p>Chapter VIII is a referrals section, listing medical facilities, mental health counseling, police departments, temporary 
emergency housing, legal information, and support networks in Santa Clara County, as well as out of county services. </p>
<p>Chapter IX is a bibliography of booklets and articles dealing with rape. </p>
<p>Every effort has been made to include as wide a range of services as possible. However, no list can be complete. There may 
be other services available in your community. </p>
